<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, Portugal to Sign Agreement on East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia and Portugal
will sign an agreement early next month on East Timor, ending long
years of hard negotiations, officials from both sides and the
United Nations announced here Friday.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, sitting at a press
conference between Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas and his
Portuguese counterpart, Jaime Gama, said that the agreement has
been finalized and will be signed together with its annex in New
York on May 5.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers hailed the agreement as a step toward
restoring peace and stability in the island country, which has
been locked in internal conflicts in the past decades.
</P>
<P>
Gama on his part said that "the effectiveness of the agreement
we are going to sign on May 5 is crucial to restoring stability
and peace in the territory." Alatas said that he was pleased to
have achieved the agreement and two additional documents with his
Portuguese counterpart.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will address the need for autonomy in the former
Portuguese colony and the two additional documents will deal with
security arrangements and modality of consultations.
</P>
<P>
Either side was willing to give details so far.
</P>
<P>
As for the security matters, Alatas said that laying down arms
and ceasing hostilities by all parties concerned will be the first
step, which is to be followed by disarmament.
</P>
<P>
He refused to give a firm date for the implementation of the
consultation agreement, but he reaffirmed that his country is
willing to carry it out as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
Under the auspices of the United Nations, the two foreign
ministers discussed for the first time this week the security
arrangements and modality of consultation. Alatas said that
although he sees no problem with the context, he has to seek final
approval from his government.
</P>
<P>
Asked if a U.N. presence is necessary for monitoring the
process, the Indonesian foreign minister gave a definite and
positive answer. But he ruled out the possibility of stationing
U.N. peacekeeping forces in the island country.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. presence will be there and this is precisely the
subject of the modality paper," Atalas said, adding "there are
many ways of U.N. presence" and foreign troops are not considered.
</P>
<P>
Pushed to comment on the proposed dispatching of U.N.
peacekeeping forces to East Timor, Atalas said that the issue has
never been on the table so far.
</P>
<P>
Jamsheed Marker, U.N. mediator on East Timor, confirmed that
the parties concerned will continue to work on what shape the U.N
presence should take.
</P>
<P>
Atalas stressed that the Indonesian military and police should
take the main responsibility of maintaining order and stability in
East Timor, while Marker echoed that diplomacy should be given
opportunity of success before considering sending in troops.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian foreign minister hailed the cease-fire accord
signed by all parties in East Timor Wednesday as a "very important
development" which, he hoped, would create a "conducive situation"
to the implementation of the agreements.
</P>
<P>
Under the cease-fire accord, the warring factions agreed to set
up a peace and stability commission, which will mainly take the
responsibility of collecting arms, according to Atalas.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief, who rushed to another meeting before the end of
the press conference, said that he is "grateful for the customary
spirit of cooperation and statesmanship displayed by the two
ministers, which has enabled us to make such progress." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
