<HEADLINE> Study: Computer Technique Could Cut Smear Test Errors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A semi-automated computer system
developed to analyze cervical smears could decrease numbers of
screening errors and improve productivity, according to a new
study published Friday.
</P>
<P>
The system, called PAPNET, uses artificial intelligence to
identify abnormal smears and check negative slides.
</P>
<P>
Reporting in the medical journal The Lancet, Professor Dulcie
Coleman and researchers, at Imperial College of Medicine in
London, described how the system performed when used to carry out
the first analysis of cervical smears not previously checked by
the human eye.
</P>
<P>
They analyzed 21,700 cervical smears from five centers in the
UK using PAPNET-assisted screening and conventional microscopic
screening to compare the two methods.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the two methods showed agreement in results for about
90 percent of all smears classified as adequate for reporting.
</P>
<P>
However, PAPNET-assisted screening was found significantly
better than conventional screening for correct identification of
negative smears.
</P>
<P>
And the time taken to screen and report the results of smears
was much shorter with PAPNET-assisted screening than with
conventional screening.
</P>
<P>
The researchers believed that use of PAPNET-assisted screening
could increase "quality and productivity" of primary screening.
</P>
<P>
"We recommend carefully organized and controlled development
projects for the introduction of PAPNET-assisted primary screening
of cervical smears," they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
