<HEADLINE> France Considers Yugoslav Proposal Insufficient </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
said Friday that the proposal by Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic on a political solution to the conflict is "entirely
insufficient" but not useless.
</P>
<P>
During a press point in Washington where he was attending a
NATO summit marking the 50th anniversary of the alliance, Chirac
said that France supports the mission by former Russian Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
"France always supports the involvement of Russia in search for
a political solution to the crisis, so we are happy about the
voyage (by Chernomyrdin)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav President Milosevic has made a six-point proposal
including an "international presence" in Kosovo under the guide of
the U.N. and with the participation of Russia, a possible
reduction of Serb troops and police force in Kosovo, and the
guarantee for a safe return of Kosovo refugees to their homes.
</P>
<P>
"What Mr. Milosevic said is entirely insufficient. I don't say
that it is useless at all, but that does not correspond to the
demands by the international community, such as those which have
been expressed by the Secretary General of the U.N.," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
He called on Russia to continue its diplomatic efforts engaging
the Yugoslav authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
