<HEADLINE> WFP Launches New Operation to Help Famine People in DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World
Food Program (WFP) had approved a new 260 million U.S. dollar
emergency operation to help feed for a year 8 million people hit
by famine in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), a
U.N. release said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The new operation targets the largest number of people since
the WFP began fighting famine in the country in late 1995.
</P>
<P>
A nutritional survey last year showed that acute malnutrition
affected about 16 percent of children between the ages of six and
seven years while chronic malnutrition or stunting affected 62
percent, reflecting the impact of the long-term food shortage.
</P>
<P>
The new one-year emergency operation starts on July 1 and will
cost 260.34 million dollars. It is aimed at a total of 8,044,000
people, including 1,470,000 children from six months to four years
old in nurseries, 655,000 kindergarten children between five and
six, 1,362,000 primary school children between seven and 11 years,
1,947,000 secondary school children between the ages of 12 and 17
and 10,000 orphans up to 17.
</P>
<P>
In addition to children identified as the most vulnerable, the
operation also seeks to supply food to 120,000 hospital patients,
320,000 pregnant and nursing women, 1,650,000 people in the WFP's
"food for work" projects and their dependents and 500,000 people
over 60 years old.
</P>
<P>
It is the fifth consecutive emergency operation mounted in the
country by the WFP. The last operation, which began in April 1998
and ends on June 30 this year, was aimed at 6.7 million
beneficiaries with 602,972 metric tons of food at a total cost of
345 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
