<HEADLINE> France Opposes Sea Blockade to Cut Oil Supply to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- France is opposed to a sea blockade
by NATO in the Adriatic Sea to cut oil supply to Yugoslavia, and
prefers to cut transport lines between Serbia and Montenegro,
which is Yugoslavia's only sea exit.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac said Friday that a sea blockade
against Yugoslavia does not have legal basis, and that it is more
efficient to impose an oil embargo on Yugoslavia by destroying the
bridges between Serbia and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
Both NATO and the European Union have imposed an oil embargo on
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Chirac made the statement at the NATO summit in Washington
which opened Friday, said local media reports.
</P>
<P>
The French president again called on NATO to study his proposal
to air drop food and medicines to the displaced people in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He also asked the alliance to be "very careful" about its
relationship with Russia, and to watch closely the situation in
Montenegro, according to the reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
