<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Farmers, Suppliers Urged Not to Hoard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Ministry of
Trade and Industry Friday advised coffee producers, suppliers and
exporters in the country not to store coffee away.
</P>
<P>
Vice Minister Brook Debebe told local press that hoarding
coffee cold result in significant loss for the producers and
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
"If coffee producers, suppliers and exporters hoard coffee in
the hope of making a profit through future changes in the value of
coffee, they are in for a disaster," the Ethiopian News Agency
quoted Brook as saying
</P>
<P>
The vice minister noted that the world price of coffee has
slumped down by 30 percent over the last eight months.
</P>
<P>
Farmers and suppliers supplied less than 79 percent of the
130,410 tons of coffee originally envisaged to reach the central
auction over the last nine months, he said.
</P>
<P>
The amount of coffee supplied during the first nine months of
1998/99 was 14 percent and 21 percent less than that of same
periods of 1997/98 and 1996/98 respectively, he said.
</P>
<P>
Brook said that 170.8 million U.S. dollars were obtained from
the export of 60,000 tons of coffee over the last nine months.
</P>
<P>
He added that the money obtained from coffee export this year
was 38 percent and 21 percent less than that of the same periods
of 1997/98 and 1996/97 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The vice minister attributed the fluctuation in the price of
coffee and failure on the part of producers to supply the crop to
the central auction to the fall in the amount of coffee revenue.
</P>
</TEXT>
