<HEADLINE> NATO Statement Sets Conditions for End of Air Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- NATO would intensify its its
air strikes against Yugoslavia unless President Slobodan Milosevic
accepted its five conditions on the settlement of the Kosovo
crisis, a NATO statement said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued at the conclusion of a three-hour session
of the first day of the NATO 50th anniversary summit said: "There
can be no compromise on these conditions."
</P>
<P>
The conditions imposed by the Western alliance include
Yugoslavia's withdrawal from its sovereign territory of Kosovo
province and NATO's presence there for so-called peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
"NATO is prepared to suspend its air strikes once Belgrade has
unequivocally accepted the above mentioned conditions and
demonstrably begun to withdraw its forces from Kosovo according to
a precise and rapid timetable," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said NATO was "putting in place additional
measures to tighten the constraints" on Belgrade, including
economic sanctions and an oil embargo, and asked defense ministers
to seek ways of halting the delivery of war material, "including
by launching maritime operations."
</P>
<P>
The statement declared that "NATO is determined to prevail,"
but it makes no mention of a possible use of ground troops prior
to a peace agreement and shunned the ethnic Albanians' demand for
independence, reaffirming that they should "enjoy substantial
autonomy within the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
The NATO leaders said in the statement that they would seek a
U.N. Security Council resolution "requiring the withdrawal of Serb
forces and the demilitarization of Kosovo and encompassing the
deployment of an international military force to safeguard the
swift return of all refugees and displaced persons."
</P>
<P>
That would likely set up a confrontation with Russia, which has
veto power in the Security Council and has strongly opposed the
NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
But they said they were still willing to seek to work
constructively with Russia, as Russia has "an important role to
play in a search for a solution to the conflict in Kosovo."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
