<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fly Control by Spray Reduces Eye Disorder: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The major cause of preventable
blindness could be significantly reduced by an insecticide spray
to control the spread of flies, researchers said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The researchers, led by Paul Emerson of the Medical Research
Council in The Gambia, have looked at links between flies and
trachoma, the leading cause of preventable blindness worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Trachoma, a bacterial infection of the upper eyelid, occurs
when eyes become infected with the bacterium Chlamydia
trachomatis, which is transmitted from one person to another by
flies landing on the face.
</P>
<P>
The disorder, most common in hotter countries, affects more
than 150 million people, mostly in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
In their research, Emerson and colleagues studied the effects
of fly control by insecticide spray deltamethrin on the prevalence
of trachoma and childhood diarrhoea in two villages in The Gambia.
</P>
<P>
The insecticide was sprayed for three months to control flies
in one village, while the other village acted as a control.
</P>
<P>
Writing in the medical journal The Lancet, the researchers
reported that after three months of fly control, there were 75
percent fewer new cases of trachoma in the villages in which
deltamethrin spray was used.
</P>
<P>
They also found that children in the sprayed villages had a 22
percent lower risk of diarrhoea than those in the control villages
in the wet season, and 26 percent lower risk of diarrhoea in the
dry season.
</P>
<P>
"Spraying would be a useful adjunct to trachoma-elimination
strategies, but further research on sustainable fly-control
methods is needed," the researchers concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Peace Talks to be Resumed This Year: British </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- British Minister of State at the
Home Office Joyce Quin said Friday the aim of the international
community for Cyprus is to bring about negotiation later this
year.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference at the end of her two-day visit to
Cyprus, Quin said there is some common ground between the two
sides of the island.
</P>
<P>
However, she said she can not guarantee a push will come about
for Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Quin said her visit was to demonstrate Britain's continuing
and active commitment to international efforts to help bring
about a comprehensive settlement on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
She said international community would like to see the
"substance of all aspects of the settlement addressed in depth
and without preconditions."
</P>
<P>
However, Quin emphasized that "ultimately, whether a solution
to Cyprus' problem can be agreed depends on Cypriots and their
leaders, no-one can impose a settlement from outside."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey
invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash opted out of the peace
talks in summer 1997 and later proposed to establish a
confederation of two equal states on the island, which is staunchly
opposed by international community.
</P>
<P>
Quin said that she has stressed in her talks here that if
either side insists on preconditions that are unacceptable to the
other, negotiations will not begin.
</P>
<P>
She reiterated Britain's support for U.N. resolutions, which
envisage reuniting the island by a bi-zonal, bi-communal
federation formula.
</P>
<P>
This is Quin's first visit to the island in her official
capacity, during which she had meetings with Cyprus President
Glafcos Clerides, Rauf Denktash and other officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
