<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Visit to Open New Chapter in Ties: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said Friday that his just-concluded visit to Russia will
begin a new chapter in Pakistan-Russia relations in the days
ahead.
</P>
<P>
"I have the understanding that a new chapter is opening. A new
leaf will be turned in Pak-Russian bilateral relations. And we
should expect better changes in the future," Sharif told reporters
upon arrival back from a four-day official visit to Russia.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the outcome of his visit, the first by a
Pakistani prime minister in 25 years, Sharif said its result could
be gauged by what has been stated by Russian President Boris
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin described Sharif's visit as a "historic event," adding
that he was "fully satisfied" with his meeting with the Pakistani
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
During his 45-minute meeting with Sharif in the Kremlin on
Wednesday, Yeltsin said: "As of today, we leave our past behind
and buried and take a new step in our relations."
</P>
<P>
On the Jammu and Kashmir issue between Pakistan and India,
Sharif said "Russia had a good opportunity to understand
Pakistan's point of view" during his visit. "We have definitely
used this opportunity in a positive way. We have said this too,
that you (Russia) play a role in resolving the Kashmir problem."
</P>
<P>
"A great potential exists between Pakistan and Russia for
cooperation in various fields" and "both countries are ready for
it," Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the two countries agreed to give
most-favored-nation treatment to each other in the matter of
trade.
</P>
<P>
A trade agreement was signed between them on Tuesday to replace
a barter trade agreement inked in 1956.
</P>
<P>
Asked what was the viewpoint of Russia on nuclear and missile
tests by Pakistan, Nawaz Sharif said: "It was the same reaction or
point of view which they had expressed" earlier.
</P>
<P>
Russia had expressed its concern over the nuclear tests by
Pakistan in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan made it clear that it was forced to test nuclear
devices to protect its vital security interests and correct the
regional imbalance created by Indian blasts.
</P>
<P>
It also test-fired its Ghauri-II and Shaheen ballistic missiles
in response to the Indian test-firing of the Agni-II earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Russia, Sharif also held a meeting with
Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
