<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Write off Mozambique's Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will write off eight
million U.S. dollars Mozambican debt, South African Financial
Minister Trevor Manuel said said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The minister, who is on a two-day visit to Mozambique, made
the announcement at a joint press conference with his Mozambican
counterpart Tomaz Salomao.
</P>
<P>
Manuel said that it is natural for South Africa to remit
Mozambique's debt, as both South Africa and Mozambique have been
urging creditor nations for further relief of debt. The relief,
though symbolic, can be taken as a signal to other creditor
nations, Salomao said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that Mozambique's total foreign debt reaches as
much as 5.5 billion U.S. dollars. But as a candidate for the
"highly indebted poor country initiative", most of the country's
foreign debt will be relieved.
</P>
<P>
Salomao said that Mozambique is expected to have its debt
reduced to 1. 1 billion dollars after debt relief decision is
finalized in this May.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the two financial ministers will also
discuss issues concerning the development of an industrial
corridor, Panda gas field in Mozambique and the pipe designed from
Mozambique's gas field to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
They will also talk, among other issues, a joint agricultural
development program in northern Mozambique's Niassa Province,
which has been plagued with problems.  
</P>
</TEXT>
