<HEADLINE> NATO Draft Declaration Sets Conditions for End of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- NATO would suspend its air
strikes against Yugoslavia only when President Slobodan Milosevic
accepted its five conditions on the settlement of the Kosovo
crisis, a European diplomat said Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said NATO was drafting a declaration to be issued by NATO
leaders at their 50th anniversary summit in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The draft declaration would back German proposals by saying the
NATO leaders were "prepared to suspend the air strikes after a
clear agreement by Belgrade on the conditions and after the
beginning of a withdrawal" of Yugoslav troops from the province.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat quoted the draft declaration as saying NATO was
"determined to stop this campaign of terror" and bring about a
"democratic, multiethnic Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
The draft called for an intensification of the air strikes and
stronger economic sanctions against Yugoslavia, including an oil
embargo, but made no mention of the option of sending ground
troops into Kosovo before a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
It threated Milosevic with "serious consequences" by continuing
to resist NATO's demands. 
