<HEADLINE> PM: Turkey to Take Measures Against Missile Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit said Friday that Turkey will take necessary measures to
prevent possible threat from the deployment of Russian-made
missiles on a Greek island.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit told reporters that "Turkey is in a position to take all
the necessary technical measures to prevent the possible threat
from the Greek deployment of the S-300 missiles on its Grete
Island."
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after Greece confirmed Thursday that a
Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft system, which was originally
destined for Cyprus, has begun being assembled on the Greek island.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit said that the move of Greece will be detrimental to
itself.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, Greek politicians regard Turkey as a danger and
are taking steps against Turkey, he said.
</P>
<P>
Greece and the Cypriot government decided last December to
deploy the S-300 missile system on Greece's Grete island, leaving
Turkey out of its range to avoid provocation.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry deputy spokesman Sermet Atacanli has
said that "the deployment of S-300 missiles on Crete will add a
new problem into the existing complicated relations between
Turkey and Greece."
</P>
<P>
"Thus it can't be accepted that this policy of Greeks and
Greek Cypriots is very accurate and rational," said Atacanli.
</P>
<P>
The delivery of the missiles had been put off several times
under Turkish and international pressure.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriots-controlled north after Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the
island in 1974 in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
</TEXT>
