<HEADLINE> Retrenchments Still High In S'pore: Union Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A Singapore union leader said
Friday that retrenchments were still high in his country although
there were signs of economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Heng Chee How, assistant secretary-general of the National
Trades Union Congress, said that a total of 1,527 workers from 47
companies had lost their jobs so far this year and three companies
planned to lay off 138 more shortly.
</P>
<P>
Heng also said the first quarter of this year saw a total of
1,179 retrenchments in the unionized sector, still higher than the
pre-economic crisis level.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that there were 678 retrenchments in the
unionized sector in the first quarter of 1996, 568 in the same
period of 1997 and 4,309 in the same quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
Heng said the figure shows "the worst is not over."
</P>
<P>
"We must continue to be mindful of the state of the economy
which remains uncertain," he said.
</P>
<P>
Heng also noted that total wage increases (including bonus)
continue their downward trend.
</P>
<P>
The National Semiconductors Pte Ltd (NS) Thursday announced its
decision to lay off 165 employees, 10 percent of the company's
workforce. 
</P>
