<HEADLINE> NATO Widens Airstrikes Against Yugoslav Civilian Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) sea-launched cruise missiles struck two
electric power transformers in the Belgrade area overnight,
marking a further escalation of NATO's air campaign, the U.S.
Defense Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"It is a new class of targets," Pentagon spokesman Kenneth
Bacon told a briefing at which he announced that allied warplanes
flew 434 missions Thursday despite bad weather.
</P>
<P>
The electric power transformers were struck by Tomahawk cruise
missiles, which use satellites for precise guidance.
</P>
<P>
Bacon said the electrical power sites also served residential
and business customers but were struck because they supply power
to military command and control facilities linked to the Yugoslav
army.
</P>
<P>
Bacon also announced that the Pentagon had decided not to add a
second aircraft carrier to the NATO naval force attacking
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The USS Theodore Roosevelt battle group is operating in the
NATO campaign, along with British and French carriers. Strike
aircraft from the Roosevelt attacked a column of seven Yugoslav
armored personnel carriers overnight and apparently inflicted
heavy damage, Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
The month-long NATO air campaign had heavily damaged roads,
bridges and resupply depots, as well as important communications
systems and significant percentages of Serb weaponry, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton has called NATO's plans to update
its ground invasion scenario "a wise and prudent course," but
stressed that NATO intended to stick with the air campaign and had
no intention of launching a ground offensive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
