<HEADLINE> Annan Hails Agreement On East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Friday hailed an agreement on East Timor, saying that
he was looking forward to concluding this historic process.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached Friday morning between Indonesian
Foreign Minister Ali Atalas and his Portugal counterpart, Jaime
Gama, after productive and successful rounds of talks which were
brokered by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The agreement has been finalized and will be signed together
with its annex in New York on May 5, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Annan said: "I look forward to
concluding this historic process on the 5th May, when all these
agreements will be signed."
</P>
<P>
"I am grateful for the customary spirit of cooperation and
statesmanship displayed by the two ministers, which has enabled us
to make such progress," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"I welcome the reaffirmation by the Indonesian government that
it will effectively carry out its responsibility for law and order
and the protection of civilians," the U.N. chief said.
</P>
<P>
"I should also underline the responsibility of all the parties
who signed an agreement this week to end the violence in East
Timor to fulfill their obligations without delay. Peace and
stability are vital in East Timor," he added.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia occupied East Timor in 1975 after Portugal pulled
out, but its right to the territory has never been recognized
internationally. 
</P>
