<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Oil Price Hike May Fuel Philippines' Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Pilipinas Shell Petroleum Corp.
joined the oil price increase bandwagon on Thursday night when it
raised its prices by an average of 43 centavos per liter.
</P>
<P>
Caltex and Petron, the other two of the three biggest oil
companies of the Philippines, have already adjusted its prices by
an average of 50 centavos and 47 centavos respectively.
</P>
<P>
Reynaldo Gamboa, vice president of Shell, said Thursday that
the price hike was mainly due to the movement of world crude
prices.
</P>
<P>
The oil firms hinted that there could be another round of
increases in the next few days, especially if the uptrend in crude
prices is sustained.
</P>
<P>
From about 10.50 U.S. dollars per barrel last February, crude
prices rose to an average of 12.45 U.S. dollars per barrel in
March and reached 15 U.S. dollars per barrel early this month
after the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries cut down
production by 2.1 million barrels in a bid to raise prices.
</P>
<P>
As a rule of thumb, an increase or decrease by a dollar in
crude prices translates into an adjustment of 30 centavos per
liter in pump prices.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, oil prices either go up or down 10 centavos per liter
for every 1 peso gained or dropped versus the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Using this as the basis for computing the needed adjustment,
the oil price increase should be about 1.20 pesos per liter.
</P>
<P>
In response to the price hike, the Department of Trade and
Industry said President Joseph Estrada has ordered all relevant
agencies to take steps in protecting consumers from the expected
spiral effect of the oil price hike.
</P>
<P>
However, Trade Secretary Jose Pardo said the government cannot
stop oil firms from increasing prices, although they can be
reminded of their commitment to the public.
</P>
<P>
"The oil industry is now fully deregulated. As much as
possible, we allow market forces to govern, not wanting to
intervene, unless there is evidence of collusion or exploitation,"
Pardo said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, some economists are worrying that the new
increases in prices of petroleum products are bound to put
pressure on the prices of other consumer goods to also move up,
although a recovery in the agricultural sector could still bring
food prices-- and the overall inflation rate--down in April.
</P>
<P>
They said the direct impact of higher fuel prices on the
consumer price index (CPI) or inflation rate will be minimal. But
they are concerned more about the indirect impact of higher fuel
prices -- such as higher transportation cost -- on food prices.
</P>
<P>
"Still the direct impact of oil on the inflation basket is very
small, but the question is how do we quantify the indirect effect
of higher oil prices on food prices," said Bankers Association of
the Philippines chief economist Johnny Noe Ravallo.
</P>
<P>
Economists said food prices have a bigger impact on inflation,
but they are watching how the higher fuel costs will affect food
prices.
</P>
<P>
If the oil price hike triggers corresponding increases in
transport fares and prices of prime commodities, the inflation
rate for April might be higher than the predicted 8.3 percent
level, the economists said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Finalizes 1999 Budget Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The red-green coalition government
in Bonn presented Friday the year 1999's budget plan, the first
one since the cabinet took over the power last autumn.
</P>
<P>
The budget calls for a spending of 485.7 billion marks (264
billion U.S. dollars), 1.2 percent up from last year. The spending
rise is lower than the rate of 1.7 percent foreseen in the
original bill.
</P>
<P>
Allocation for social welfare will rise to 172.4 billion marks,
an increase of nearly 10 billion marks from 1998.
</P>
<P>
New state borrowing is to be restricted at 53.5 billion marks.
Originally it has been set at 56.2 billion marks.
</P>
<P>
Experts of the ruling Social Democratic Party (SPD) said part
of Bonn's spending, about 20 billion marks, should be covered by
privatizing the state's holdings to shape up Germany's finance.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was backed by the Greens Party, junior partner
that shares power with Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's SPD.
</P>
<P>
The budget, finalized much later than normal due to government
changeover, will be sent to the parliament in early May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
