<HEADLINE> NATO Summit Decides to Impose Oil Embargo on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) summit decided here Friday to tighten economic
sanctions against Yugoslavia by imposing an embargo on petroleum
products to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after they met for three hours to discuss
the crisis in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, leaders of the 19
NATO member countries stopped short of imposing a full naval
blockade on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
However, they asked their defense ministers to study ways to
halt through "maritime operations" the shipment of war supplies to
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
France opposed a full naval blockade on the grounds that NATO
would violate international law, a NATO official said.
</P>
<P>
Also Friday, the European Union (EU) formally adopted a
decision to impose a ban on deliveries of oil and oil products to
Yugoslavia by EU member nations.
</P>
<P>
NATO airstrikes have put Serbia's two oil refineries out of
operation in an effort to cut off fuel supplies to Serbian troops
in Kosovo. However, petroleum supplies have not been completely
cut off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists Optimistic About Asian Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Five economics who read their
papers Friday at the Asia Forum 1999 all expressed optimism about
the economic outlook for Asia this year, forecasting economic
contraction will come to a stop this year.
</P>
<P>
The forum was jointly organized by Singapore's Institute of
Southeast Asian Study (ISEAS) and Japan's Nomura Research
Institute to discuss the prospect of Asian recovery and financial
reforms.
</P>
<P>
Jungho Yoo, vice president of the Development Institute of
South Korea, told the forum that given the trends in consumption
and investment in his country, it seems likely that South Korea's
economy will register about two percent growth in 1999 compared
with the 5.6 percent contraction in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Hitoshi Okuda, director of the Center for Knowledge Exchange
and Creation, Nomura Research Institute, said he forecasts his
country's economy will stop shrinking around the end of 1999 as
adjustments in domestic private-sector demand run their course.
</P>
<P>
As current improvement in the Japanese economy is basically
only temporary and the economy will require a more structural
adjustments, he forecasts a growth rate of minus 1.3 percent,
lower than the government's forecast of positive 0.5 percent
growth.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xiaoji, director-general of the Research Department of
Foreign Economic Relations of the Development Research Center of
the State Council of China, told the forum that the momentum of
China's economic development is quite good and China can realize
the target of seven percent growth in 1999.
</P>
<P>
To support his view, Zhang expounded on China's policies on
expanding domestic demand and the reform of state-owned
enterprises as well as on measures to prevent financial risks and
keep the RMB's exchange rate stable.
</P>
<P>
Edward K Y Chen, president of Lingnan College, Hong Kong,
predicted Hong Kong's economy will achieve a growth rate of two
percent which is in striking contrast with the negative growth
forecast by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Chen said he made such a prediction partly because of
improvement in Hong Kong's internal economic fundamentals and in
the external economic environment, and partly because of
statistical effects. The dramatic fall in GDP in 1998 means a very
low base for 1999 to benchmark on, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Chao-cheng Mai, president of Chun-Hua Institution for Economic
Research in Taiwan, predicted Taiwan's economy will grow 4.97
percent in 1999, among the lowest growth rates in the history of
the development of the Taiwan economy.
</P>
<P>
Summing up, ISEAS Director Chia Siow Yue said Asian economies
have bottomed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
