<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR Lacks Funds for Repatriation of Afghan Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Officials from the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) said here Friday that they are
facing financial problems repatriation of Afghan refugees from
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Despite the continued desire of substantial numbers of Afghan
refugees to return to their homes, the UNHCR suffered its
worst-ever funding crisis for its Afghanistan program during 1998,
and the outlook for 1999 is bleak, they said.
</P>
<P>
According to a U.N. refugee bulletin, funding for refugee
repatriation and reintegration had virtually dried up altogether
by October last year, even though Afghans were the largest
assisted returnee group anywhere in the world with 107,000
returnees going back with UNCHR assistance in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The shortage of funds has already damaged the momentum and
credibility of the new group repatriation scheme. And even more
seriously, some refugee groups, who went home earlier in 1998, are
threatening to return to Pakistan, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Susan Manuel, a spokesperson for the World Food
Program, said here Friday at a press briefing that about 20,000
Afghan refugees living in Pakistan will face starvation if the WFP
does not get funds.
</P>
<P>
The emergency aid would be terminated to the Afghan refugees on
April 30 unless the WFP gets new funds, she said.
</P>
<P>
Guillermo Bottoechi, a senior official from the UNHCR in
Islamabad, said 100,000 Afghan refugees had been returning
annually with the help of the UNHCR. But the process has slowed
down because of lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
"We have stopped all UNHCR assistance to individual refugees,"
he said, adding that assistance is now provided on a community
basis to make the refugees self-reliant.
</P>
<P>
According to the UNHCR, about 7,500 refugees have been
repatriated so far this year and the figure is expected to reach
10,000 by the end of June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
