<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Opens 50th Anniversary Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- NATO leaders of 19 member
countries Friday opened a 50th anniversary summit obsessed by
troubles of desperate air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The war engaged by NATO in Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia,
has changed what was to have been a jubilant celebration into a
crisis summit on how best to force the Yugoslav forces to pull out
of the province.
</P>
<P>
After failure to drive the Yugoslav troops out of Kosovo by
five-week bombing, NATO was considering a possible invasion of the
province by sending ground troops there.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said in opening remarks to
the assembled leaders that Europe was "confronting a very serious
crisis."
</P>
<P>
NATO has obviously shifted its previous functions of taking
actions within its boundary and has now adopted what it called a
new concept: waging an outside-territorial war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the NATO summit, Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic had signaled through a Russian diplomat a willingness to
allow some international presence in Kosovo, but Western leaders
insisted on having an armed peacekeeping force in the province.
</P>
<P>
Solana threatened that Milosevic must accept NATO's demand or
face continued bombings.
</P>
<P>
"Milosevic must know there is no place for his policies in
Europe on the eve of the 21st century," he said.
</P>
<P>
The use of NATO ground troops is now taken into consideration
as NATO's air strikes have yielded no apparent results as NATO
leaders had expected.
</P>
<P>
The issue of sending ground troops is surely a topic to be
discussed by major NATO leaders even though a NATO official denied
it a formal subject "on the agenda."
</P>
<P>
NATO Supreme Allied Commander Gen. Wesley Clark was given
authority Wednesday to lead a study on how many troops it would
take to drive the Serbs from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Beside the issue of the Kosovo crisis, NATO leaders were also
expected to adopt decisions on other issues, including an update
of NATO's strategy for the 21st century, recognition of a greater
role for Europe within the alliance and a reaffirmation of NATO's
commitment to keep its door open to new members from Central and
Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
The summit meeting was under extraordinary security.
Washington's central downtown area was cordoned off for security
reasons. To minimize traffic gridlock for the summit, thousands of
federal employees were given the day off. Schools were closed, as
well as many businesses in the downtown security zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
