<HEADLINE> Clinton Announces 1.5 Mln Dlr Aid to Shooting Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Clinton Friday
announced a sum of 1.5 million dollars as financial assistance to
the victims of the Colorado school shooting.
</P>
<P>
The president said the money, which was drawn from the federal
Crime Victims' Fund, was an initial payment to help the students,
teachers and parents affected by the slaying on "their long
journey toward recovery. And we will do more."
</P>
<P>
"The images from Colorado have become painfully familiar: the
terrified children, the racing ambulances, the grieving families,"
Clinton said at the White House.
</P>
<P>
"Still, it is important to remember that the vast majority of
schools are safe," he added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton reminded school officials across the country of federal
programs to help prevent violent eruptions of rage, such as the
two students unleashed inside Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Vice President Al Gore was traveling to Colorado to
attend memorial services of the killed in the most serious school
shooting in America's history. As many as 15 people, including the
two teenage gunmen, were killed in Tuesday's campus tragedy.
</P>
