<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Tokyo's New Governor Must Be Cautious in Making Statements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The newly-inaugurated governor of
Tokyo, Shintaro Ishihara, after repeatedly making erroneous
statements detrimental to Sino-Japan friendship, is still
persisting in his anti-China stance, wantonly intervening in
China's internal affairs, and attacking China's policy on Taiwan
and Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Since Friday is the first day of Ishihara's term as governor of
Tokyo, people are expecting him, an official who holds the most
important local government post in Japan, to make a fresh start,
refrain from making erroneous speeches which will hurt Chinese
people's feelings and shift to the position of maintaining Sino-
Japan friendship.
</P>
<P>
However, at a press conference following his inauguration
Friday, Ishihara continued his erroneous stance on the Tibet and
Taiwan issues, making groundless charges against China's central
government's policy toward Tibet and Taiwan and distorting China's
policy of peacefully reuniting the motherland with Taiwan, while
not ruling out the use of force.
</P>
<P>
As is known to all, China has long been a multi-national
country, and Tibet and Taiwan are inalienable parts of China's
sacred territory. Most countries, including Japan, have all
recognized and observe the "One China" policy, while respecting
China's principled stand related to national sovereignty. Under
the Japan-China Joint Statement and Japan-China Peace and
Friendship Treaty, the Japanese side confirmed principles of
mutual respect of sovereignty and territorial integrity, and all
the successive governments of Japan abided by the "one China"
policy.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu Nonaka, in response to
Ishihara's anti-China speeches, pointed out on April 19 that Japan
would not change its policy toward China. He said Japan would
continue to carry out principles enshrined in the Japanese-China
Joint Statement and continue to develop good neighborly relations
with China, one of the major Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
As a newly inaugurated local official, Ishihara made
irresponsible statements on a major issue concerning China's
unification and sovereignty, completely in disregard of the
Japanese government's China policy.
</P>
<P>
As such anti-China statements by Ishihara have once again
seriously impaired the development of Sino-Japan relations, they
will undoubtedly cause indignation and alarm to the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
An out and out hawkish figure in the political circles of Japan
with ultra-rightist political leaning, Ishihara advocates the
revision of the Japanese Constitution of peace.
</P>
<P>
He stubbornly clung to the reactionary historical view, while
spouting odd opinions in respect to Japan's relations with China.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, Ishitara denied Japan's history of
aggression toward China. He also labeled the notorious 1937
Nanjing Massacre as a "lie fabricated by Chinese."
</P>
<P>
Even now, more than 50 years after the end of the Second World
War, he still addresses China by the name of "Sina," a derogatory
and discriminating name habitually used by the Japanese aggressor
troops during their war of aggression against China.
</P>
<P>
Ishitara's political statements and actions have been condemned
and despised by peace-loving Japanese people.
</P>
<P>
At this stage, it seems extraordinarily difficult for Ishihara
to change his political view. Since Ishihara is the current
governor of Japan's capital and a senior Japanese government
functionary, it is reasonable for him to comply with the Japanese
government's persistent policy on China, and keep his senses on
major issues relevant to the overall of China-Japan friendship.
</P>
<P>
We would like to advice Ishihara to earnestly study and adhere
to the principles and spirit set by the Sino-Japan Joint Statement
and the China-Japan Peace and Friendship Treaty, refrain from
releasing further statement that will hurt the Chinese people's
feeling or doing anything that will undermine the friendship for
generations to come between the Chinese and Japanese people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
