<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's Antitrust Commission is likely to join in
a one billion shekels (about 250 million U.S. dollars)
class-action suit filed recently against several cable television
providers. The cable companies were charged of taking advantage
of their monopoly to set unfairly high fees for poor customer
service and inadequate channel offerings.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwaiti Minister of State for Housing Affairs
Jassem Al-Oun said Friday that about 11,000 new houses will be
ready for Kuwaiti applicants.
</P>
<P>
The Public Housing Authority has allocated contracts worth 40
million Kuwaiti dinars (about 132 million U.S. dollars) with
local companies to equip these residential units, Al-Oun said in
an interview with Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said that applicants for new houses have reached 50,000,
noting that the new houses will help ease growing demand for
housing by Kuwaiti families.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait, which enforces a cradle-to-grave welfare policy,
provides free housing through different housing programs for
families and citizens covered by government housing care.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The slowdown in industry, construction, hotels,
transportation and communications continued into the first quarter
of 1999, said a poll of companies conducted by the Bank of
Israel. But trade companies reported stability and said they
expect increasing sales during the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The Lebanese government collected 187 billion pounds
(about 124 million U.S. dollars) from customs duties in March this
year, according to the country's customs authorities.
</P>
<P>
The March figure witnessed a 19 percent increase over that of
February and a 11 percent rise over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
But economists predicted that the revenues would fall from
April as the government imposed customs duties to up to 55 percent
on luxury items such as cheese, watches, alcohol and cigaretts.
</P>
</TEXT>
