<HEADLINE> Ishihara Needs a China Trip: Leading Japanese Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A Leading Japanese newspaper, Asahi
Shimbun, published an editorial Friday advising new Tokyo Governor
Shintaro Ishihara to go to Beijing at an early date to better
understand China.
</P>
<P>
In response to Ishihara's remarks on the Taiwan issue, Asahi
Shimbun said that Ishihara should refrain from ignoring the "One
China" policy put forth in the 1972 Sino-China Joint Statement and
the 1978 China-Japan Peace and Friendship Treaty, and dampening
the friendship between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The office of the Tokyo governor is not Ishihara's personal
property, the mass-circulated Japanese newspaper said, adding that
the damage done by Ishihara's imprudent statements would
eventually damage his ability to govern Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Ishihara, a ultra-rightist Japanese politician and writer,
flagrantly attacked the Chinese government and its policies on
Tibet and Taiwan in an interview with Japanese media after he was
elected Tokyo governor last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Ishihara, who once said he thought the notorious 1937 Rape of
Nanjing was a Chinese fabrication, said after the election that he
didn't mean it was a lie, but meant that he just did not believe
the number of people killed, the daily noted. The number of
people killed in the Rape of Nanjing, also known as the Nanjing
Massacre, has been estimated at 300,000.
</P>
<P>
In that case, why not go all the way to Nanjing, the daily
asked, adding that seeing the scene of the crime with an author's
eye for collecting historical proof would also help Ishihara
fulfill his duties as a governor.
</P>
<P>
Ishihara needs an early visit to Beijing as a governor to
frankly exchange opinions with Chinese, the daily said, adding
that whatever he might say will be not persuasive as long as he
keeps saying he does not want to visit China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
