<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Police Brutality Sparks Controversy in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A BBC documentary on
incidents of South African police brutality has caused controversy
across the country.
</P>
<P>
The documentary, aired by the BBC on Monday night, showed
police officers punching, kicking, rifle-butting and setting dogs
on arrested suspects. Part of the documentary was screened by
South African television stations on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
While the violence was officially condemned and six officers
involved were suspended, ordinary citizens tend to look at the
other side of the story.
</P>
<P>
Riaan Smit was the original victim of one of the car hijacking
incidents filmed by the BBC.
</P>
<P>
Smit was hijacked on January 24 in downtown Johannesburg. He
was approached by an armed man when he stopped his car that night
to make a U- turn.
</P>
<P>
"I got out of the car, and he swore at me and told me not to
move. So I did what he said. He stood in front of me, aimed the
gun at my head and squeezed the trigger.
</P>
<P>
"Then he looked at the gun in surprise when it jammed, shook it
a bit, pointed it into my face and pulled the trigger again, and
still nothing happened," Smit recalled with horror.
</P>
<P>
The hijacker was then joined by an accomplice and fled with
Smit's white BMW. Smit phoned the anti-hijacking flying squad and
within 30 minutes his car was spotted.
</P>
<P>
In a car chase, the stolen car crashed. The BBC footage showed
police officers punching one unconscious hijacker, who was trapped
behind the steering wheel, and hitting another with rifle butt as
he lay next to the stolen car. A gun was found inside the car.
</P>
<P>
One of the suspects died in hospital. However, it is unknown
whether he died of the crash or the assault.
</P>
<P>
"Where was the camera when the guy pointed a gun in my face and
squeezed the trigger?" Smit asked.
</P>
<P>
"I am not saying that what the police did was right, but they
acted so quickly when they spotted my car, and after the arrest
they took my cellphone, ID book and personal items, and had them
returned to me. How bad can they be?"
</P>
<P>
Smit's attitude was not alone in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Citizen newspaper Thursday carried an article by its
well-known writer Brian Stuart, asking the frequently asked
question: why criminals' human rights are better protected than
those of law-abiding citizens?
</P>
<P>
Stuart could not hide his anger at the current criminal justice
system. He asked: "Why is an injured criminal treated in hospital
at state expense, but not the person he injured? Why is a rapist
entitled to legal defense, but not his victim?
</P>
<P>
"Why is he able to lay a charge of assault against any person
who dares defend themselves against him. Why is he not required to
recompense the person for the damage done?"
</P>
<P>
"All the privileges and safeguards are those accorded to the
violators of our human rights," he commented.
</P>
<P>
Most readers' letters carried by newspapers reflect the idea
that police brutality should not be condoned but certain acts are
understandable under certain circumstances.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports, the overwhelming majority of phone
calls to TV and radio stations showed sympathy with the police,
whom they believe work under extremely high level of stress.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a total of 223 policemen were killed while on duty
and more than 1,000 officers lost their lives since 1994.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has the world's highest rape rate and its murder
rate is only next to Colombia.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, there is, on average, one
murder or attempted murder every 12 minutes and a rape every 26
seconds.
</P>
<P>
As pictures of the BBC footage could be easily compared to
scenes of apartheid-era police brutality, the authorities were
quick to condemn the incidents.
</P>
<P>
National Police Commissioner George Fivaz described the
incidents as " unacceptable and contrary to departmental
directives, our prevention of torture policy and our code of
conduct".
</P>
<P>
Gauteng provincial police commissioner, Sharma Maharaj, said
the scenes were "despicable acts of lawlessness, making a mockery
of our police service".
</P>
<P>
The officers involved have been suspended, the elite Brixton
anti- hijacking flying squad has been disbanded. An investigation
into the incidents has been launched.
</P>
<P>
However, as experts has pointed out, the problem lies with this
country' s criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
"To suspend six policemen is a simplistic solution. You need to
tackle the root cause of the problem, which lies in the criminal
justice system.
</P>
<P>
"Look at the impact of trauma and multiple exposure to so much
violence and crime, combined with the daily threat to life, and
balance that with the resulting behavior," said Mary Robertson, a
psychologist at the trauma clinic of the Center for the Study of
Violence and Reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Researcher at the center, David Bruce, said: "The police live
in a world of their own and daily come face-to-face with crime in
all its brutality, viciousness and violence. And they lack
confidence in the justice system and feel there is a lack of
seriousness from the government when it comes to tackling crime."
</P>
<P>
"The guys are left feeling that 'if we don't do something about
the problem, no one else will'."
</P>
<P>
The African National Congress government has refused to restore
the death penalty despite the fact that the majority of South
Africans favor the return of capital punishment. Nor it agrees to
hold a referendum on the issue.
</P>
<P>
It argues that such a move is against the constitution, which
states that everyone has the right to life, and that the death
penalty is not a deterrent to crime.
</P>
<P>
The death penalty was abolished shortly before the first
democratic elections in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
