<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF, World Bank to Strengthen HIPC Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) and World Bank will take actions to strengthen the
Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) Initiative, a senior IMF
official said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Tony Boote, in charge of the initiative at the IMF, said the
debt relief program for the world's most debt-ridden countries has
failed to live up to expectations and needs much work.
</P>
<P>
The HIPC Initiative, launched in the fall of 1996, represented
a major departure from past practice in dealing with debt problems
of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
It focused on achieving overall external debt-sustainability
with comprehensive participation by all external creditors for the
most heavily indebted countries with good track record.
</P>
<P>
The program initially promised debt relief to 23 countries,
with proposals to broaden it to 41 countries with total debt of
$200 billion.
</P>
<P>
However, just two countries, Bolivia and Uganda, have received
funds from the plan while only seven more have qualified for
debt-relief packages.
</P>
<P>
Critics said the tough criteria have excluded many countries,
slowed the process for years and failed to ensure debt relief.
</P>
<P>
"That is why we are trying to strengthen the initiative now and
that is why the international community is trying to work a more
effective program out," Boote said.
</P>
<P>
The program will be discussed next week at the annual spring
meetings of the IMF and World Bank in Washington.
</P>
<P>
In addition, five G-7 countries have made proposals for
changes to the program and it is expected to be discussed at the
G-7 Cologne Summit in June.

nnnn
04:14 04:14 g # NAB
</P>
</TEXT>
