<HEADLINE> Egyptian, Russian FMs Hold Talks on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers of Egypt and
Russia began talks here Friday evening on the latest developments
in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported that Amr Moussa and
Igor Ivanov are expected to focus their discussion on the peace
talks between the Palestinians and Israel, and the Palestinians'
possible declaration of statehood.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has said he will declare an
independent Palestinian state on May 4 when the five-year interim
autonomy under the Oslo Accord signed with Israel in 1993 expires.
</P>
<P>
Russia, one of the co-sponsor of the peace process besides the
United States, supports Palestinians' right to self-determination
but has reportedly advised Arafat to postpone the declaration
until after Israel's elections on May 17 to avoid complicating the
peace-making march.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers will also tackle ways of promoting
bilateral relations in various domains, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Russia maintain close ties at both the political and
economic levels. Officials of the two countries often consult and
coordinate stances on international and regional issues of mutual
concern.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov arrived here earlier in the day as part a regional tour,
which has taken him to Israel and the Palestinian self-rule
areas. He will travel on to Syria and Lebanon after wrapping up
visit here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
