<HEADLINE> Kenyan Foreign Minister on Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Foreign Minister Bonaya
Godana condemned the air strikes on Kosovo by the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) here Friday in an interview with
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Godana pointed out the practice that a group of countries
decided to ignore the United Nations and took military actions
against a sovereign country "is very frightening to a small
country like us because it reminds us of the evil gunboat
diplomacy."
</P>
<P>
"It is Yugoslavia today, and could be any other country
tomorrow," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He added that any forcibly menace or any military action by a
group of states must be legitimatized through authorization by the
U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"We are in an international organization -- the United Nations
-- committed to the purpose of maintaining international peace and
security," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Since NATO was founded as a collective defensive alliance and
there was no aggression from Yugoslavia, it is not justified for
the NATO to launch military actions against Yugoslavia," Godana
said.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the air strikes were against "not just
military targets but increasingly non-military civilian projects,
finally broadcasting stations and bridges." 
</P>
</TEXT>
