<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Set To Escape Economic Recession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Britain looks set to escape an
economic recession, but growth would be sluggish for some time,
official figures showed Friday.
</P>
<P>
Gross domestic product is estimated to have grown by 0.1
percent in the first three months of this year compared with the
previous quarter, according to the Office for National Statistics.
</P>
<P>
At an annual rate, the UK economy is growing by 0.7 percent -
under the government's forecast of growth of 1-1.5 percent for the
year.
</P>
<P>
The six interest rate cuts by the Bani of England appear to
have improved business and consumer confidence and reinvigorated
the business.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector is still suffering, but the service
sector, which now makes up three-quarters of the economy, grew by
0.4 percent, at an annual rate of 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Neil Parker, economist at Royal Bank of Scotland, said:
"Although 0.1 percent growth is nothing to shout about, it is
likely to represent the slowest growth this year, since we expect
a consumer led recovery to lead to stronger growth later."
</P>
</TEXT>
