<HEADLINE> Japanese Coach: We Can Still Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Despite the almost landslide favors
for a Spanish win at the FIFA World YOuth Championship, Japan's
French coach Philippe Troussier still kept a high profile saying
that "we can still win."
</P>
<P>
"We respect Spain but, even so, we can still win, " Troussier
said just less than 20 hours before the final match between Japan
and Spain.
</P>
<P>
"The whole of Japan is happy .... and I am happy because I
never thought we would get this far in the competition," said the
"white witch doctor".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Spanish coach, Inaki Saez Ruiz, seems to share
Troussier' s feeling of leading his team to such a surprising
position, after seeing the kicks-out of such big names as Brazil,
Portugal, Argentina, Germany and England.
</P>
<P>
"Before the tournament, this was unthinkable," said Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
But with all its tradition and history in soccer, Spain seems
to be above Japan in many people's eyes when the two clash in
Lagos in hours.
</P>
<P>
"Playing a team like Japan increases our chances of winning,
admittedly, but we can't sell the bearskin before killing the bear,
" Ruiz said.
</P>
<P>
But while both sides are surprised to see each other in the
final, the two have earned their chance with a similar confidence
by distinct, vigorous playing styles.
</P>
<P>
After losing its opener to Cameroon 2-1, the Japanese haven't
lost since, beating the United States, England, Portugal (on
penalties), Mexico and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
Spain, which is making its first appearance in the U-20 World
Cup final since losing the 1985 title game to Brazil, had a
similar march: losing 2-0 to Brazil, drawing with Zambia, before
beating Honduras, the United States, Ghana (on penalties) and Mali.
</P>
<P>
Claiming that "the pressure is on Spain, " Troussier said that
Japan "has already won by just getting to the final and knowing
that we at least have the silver."
</P>
<P>
Troussier, who had coached in Africa for many years, was
deprived of his job as the Nigerian team's coach last year after
Nigeria's "Super Eagle" performed "badly" to many Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
The "white witch doctor" won his fame back to some extend when
thousands of Nigerian fans chanted "we want Troussier" when his
Japanese boys beat Uruguay 2-1 at the semi-final.  
</P>
</TEXT>
