<HEADLINE> Violence Erupts as Kenyan Opposition Supporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- At least 10 people were injured
Saturday in the fighting between supporters of two rival
opposition leaders in Ugenya district, Nyanza province in west
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Violence erupted just as Raila Odinga started a fund-raising
rally in the constituency of his rival member of parliament James
Orengo of Ford-Kenya. The rally was considered by the followers of
Orengo as a plot to undermine the political influence of Orengo.
</P>
<P>
The rally was disrupted by Orengo's supporters and deteriorated
into a fighting so turbulent that Kenyan police fired in the air
as to control the situation, according to reports reaching here
from the province.
</P>
<P>
One supporter of Orengo was admitted to hospital after being
beaten up. A policeman was also seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
Orengo, a lawyer, is seen as a staunch critic of the
government, while Odinga serves as leader of the National
Development Party, which formed an informal alliance last year
with Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi's ruling party KANU.
</P>
<P>
Both Odinga and Orengo command a high degree of respect in
Nyanza province with inhabitants of the Luo tribe, the second
biggest tribe in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Police had blocked Ugenya town to stop Orengo staging his own
parallel rally, which had been banned by a government decree.
</P>
<P>
The conflict between the two prominent political figures in
Kenya has been the front-page news stories of local newspapers
this week. The leading newspaper Daily Nation said Saturday that
this was a disgrace over Ugenya rally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
