<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Economic Situation Stabilized: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's economic situation
has stabilized and the signs of economic revival were quite
visible, Finance Minister Ishaq Dar said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, Dar said the first three
quarters of the current fiscal year ending on June 30, 1999 posted
encouraging results on different economic fronts.
</P>
<P>
The government retired domestic debt of 43 billion rupees (935
million U.S. dollars) in the first nine months of this year
against a bank borrowing of 41 billion rupees (891 million
dollars) in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
He also said monetary expansion in the first three quarters of
the current fiscal year was maintained at 3.3 percent in the wake
of tight monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
Despite difficulties, he said, the revenue collection during
the first nine months of the current fiscal year amounted to 203.8
billion rupees (4.43 billion dollars), two percent higher than
last year's 199.7 billion rupees (4.34 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said the reduction in imports resulted in a decline of
revenue from import-related taxes such as custom duties, sales tax
and income tax.
</P>
<P>
Curtailment in development expenditure also resulted in lower
collection from direct and indirect taxes, he said.
</P>
<P>
Describing the first three quarters as the most difficult
period in the country's history, he said Pakistan was subjected to
external shocks of unprecedented nature which created serious
economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
"The export prices of major agricultural commodities and raw
materials have collapsed," Dar said. "Pakistan, being a part of
the global economy, cannot remain wholly immune to these
unfavorable development."
</P>
<P>
But he said the government's effective economic and financial
management had led the country out of the crisis in a relatively
shorter period of time compared with East Asian countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Positive Signs of Economic Improvement Emerge in HK (1) By Tao Wenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Positive signs of improvement
in the economic situation in Hong Kong have been emerging recently,
including the falling interest rates, the rebound in stock and
property prices and the increasing inflow of foreign capital and
overseas visitors.
</P>
<P>
However, the unemployment rate remains high while the value of
external trade is still on a downtrend.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Association of Banks earlier this month announced
its sixth deposit rates cut since October last year. In the
meantime, Hong Kong's major banks also reduced their prime lending
rates by 0.25 percent to 8.5 percent, the lowest level in two
years.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the rates cut is a boost to investor
confidence by way of lowering the cost for loans and would help
speed up Hong Kong's recovery process by pumping local money from
banks to the stock and property markets.
</P>
<P>
Specialists say there is still room for a further rate
reduction.
</P>
<P>
Share prices have seen sharp growth in the past weeks due to
heavy inflow of local and overseas funds.
</P>
<P>
Although the stocks failed to break the 13,000 point level at
the last minutes to the end of the week's trading session on
Friday, the share prices surged 3.32 percent in the week following
a leap of nearly 5 percent in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
The blue chip Hang Seng Index hit its highest level since
October 20, 1997 at 13,364.42 during the morning session on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Daily turnover rose up to above 10 billion HK dollars (1.28
billion U.S. dollars) in the week except on Wednesday. On Monday
and Friday turnovers reached nearly 15 billion Hong Kong dollars (
1.92 billion U.S. dollars), the highest ones since August last
year.
</P>
<P>
China-related stocks also enjoyed strong growth this week, with
the Hang Seng China Enterprises Index and the China affiliated
enterprises index growing by 11.78 percent and 10.42 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The inflow of large amount of foreign as well as local money
into the stock market reflects the level of investor confidence in
the economic prospect of Hong Kong, a regional financial center
and a gateway for foreign investors to enter the market of China's
mainland.
</P>
<P>
Asian economies hit by the financial turmoil are expected to
begin to recover in 1999 and the pace of economic growth in
China's mainland remains very firm.
</P>
<P>
As overseas investors believe China's entry into the World
Trade Organization (WTO) will take place this year, they have good
reasons to seize business opportunities in Hong Kong, the first
step to do business with firms on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
However, some experts say Hong Kong's share prices have been
overvalued and that there are some bubbles in the stock market.
The market could be volatile around the current level for a period
of time before the complete recovery of Hong Kong's economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the resumption of government land sales on April 20
was believed to be a boost to the local property market.
</P>
<P>
The land auction, conducted 10 months after the government
decided to suspend land sales in June 1998, achieved encouraging
results by raising 1.49 billion HK dollars (190 million U.S.
dollars) with a total of over 26,000 square meters of government
lots.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the better-than-expected prices demonstrate that
developers are confident of the development of the property market.
</P>
<P>
The sales gave an immediate push to property prices, with flat
owners raising asking prices in the second-hand market by 5 to 10
percent while developers rushed to put more homes on the market.
</P>
<P>
In the mean time, some developers said the prices were too high.
They fear that high property prices would dent HK's
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The government has promised to continue to provide sufficient
land supply to keep property prices stable.
</P>
<P>
The land sales were suspended at the end of June last year in
an effort to stabilize the sharply falling property prices which
had plunged by about 50 percent forced by the soaring interest
rates as a result of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
While the sharp fall in property prices might be good for home
buyers, it created problems for small and medium-sized enterprises,
accounting for more than 90 percent of firms in Hong Kong, who use
their properties as mortgages to get loans from banks.
</P>
<P>
The rebound in stock and property prices is usually faster than
the improvement of the unemployment and external trade situation.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate for January-March 1999 stood at 6.2
percent. The value of re-export and domestic export dropped by 10.
1 percent and 9.9 percent respectively in February compared with
the same month of last year while the value of import fell 24.9
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
