<HEADLINE> Iran Dismisses Human Rights Resolution as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Saturday termed a
resolution of the U.N. Human Rights Commission on the country's
human rights status as "politically motivated and illegitimate."
</P>
<P>
The resolution is another proof that the Commission's reviewing
process of human rights situation in different countries is a
political move, the Iranian Foreign Ministry Spokesman Hamid Reza
Asefi said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Human Rights Commission at an annual session in
Geneva on Friday passed a motion proposed by the European Union
(EU), expressing concerns about human rights abuses in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Iran, upholding its Islamic and cultural values, tries to
promote human rights of its citizens, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Iran maintains that the resolution has no basis for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The resolution with pre-determined political objectives has
failed to reflect the realities of the dynamic society of the
Islamic Republic of Iran, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
As before, it is seeking to raise groundless allegations
against Iran, he said. And the initiators of the resolution
overtly and officially resorted to all political and economic
leverage to attract other countries' votes against Iran.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also expressed pleasure with the oppositive
voices of many countries, including member states of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC), Non-Aligned Movement
(NAM) and several independent developing countries to the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
He said that these countries opposed the resolution and
welcomed a proposal to end monitoring human rights conditions in
Iran. 
</P>
