<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Positive Signs of Economic Improvement Emerge in HK (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the past months, foreign investors have shown great interest
in Hong Kong's telecommunication sector.
</P>
<P>
American software giant Microsoft announced last month in Hong
Kong its "strategic cooperation" with Hong Kong's major full-
service communications provider Hongkong Telecom in developing
high-speed broadband services that will allow Hong Kong to fully
experience the convergence of low-cost personal computer and
telecommunications technologies.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates, during a visit to Hong Kong,
also expressed interest in participating in the planned Cyberport
project in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The 13 billion HK dollar (1.7 billion U.S. dollar) Cyberport
project was announced by Financial Secretary Donald Tsang in his
budget address on March 3 with an aim to boost the development of
Hong Kong's information industry.
</P>
<P>
World leading Internet media company Yahoo signed an agreement
this month with Hong Kong's SmarTone Mobile Communications to
provide content for SmarTone's soon-to-be-launched Internet
service.
</P>
<P>
Yahoo Chief Jerry Yang confirmed that the group's Greater China
headquarters would be located in Hong Kong, and expressed its
intention to be part of the Cyberport effort.
</P>
<P>
On April 8, the British Telecommunications (BT) announced that
it would buy 20 percent of the enlarged shares of SmarTone.
</P>
<P>
The move by BT, one of the largest telecommunication companies
in the world, represents a 3-billion-HK dollar (384.6 million U.S.
dollars) investment in SmarTone, which makes BT SmarTone's second
largest shareholder.
</P>
<P>
The tourism industry is among the first in Hong Kong to walk
out of the shadow of the Asian financial turmoil. The total number
of visitors to Hong Kong was 861,347 in March this year, a 12.4
percent increase over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The fairs and exhibitions held recently in Hong Kong have also
been successful. There were a record 46,000 visitors to the
largest giftware trade fair in Asia -- the Hong Kong Gifts and
Houseware Fair '99 and the Hong Kong Premium Fair '99,
representing an increase of 18.3 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey conducted by the Hong Kong Policy Research
Institute on Economic Confidence Index on April 19 and 20 showed
that average public confidence in Hong Kong's economic situation
or "Prospects of Hong Kong" rose 8.1 points compared with a
similar survey conducted in March.
</P>
<P>
The confidence index of "Improvement on Unemployment Situation'
was 29.9 points higher than in March amidst the public's upbeat
approach towards the economic prospects of Hong Kong, brought
about by the successful land auction, and especially Chinese
Premier Zhu Rongji's recent successful visit to the United States
and progress in the negotiations over China's entry into the WTO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
