<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Kidnappers Set $100,000 Ransom for Italian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Somali gunmen demanded 100,000
U.S. dollars for the release of the kidnapped Italian aid worker
of the Terra Nuova, threatening that they "will take an emergency
decision unless something quick is done in the next 48 hours. "
</P>
<P>
Marwas Yareh Hassan, gunmen spokesman, made the threat in an
interview with Xinhua reporter through VHF radio, but he has
refused to elaborate what kind of decision they are likely to
take.
</P>
<P>
The Somali gunmen kidnapped Stefano Sotgia, an Italian
veterinarian aid worker for the Terra Nuova a week ago in the town
of Hagar, 165 kilometers northwest of the southern port city of
Kismayu .
</P>
<P>
The spokesman accused Terra Nuova for being responsible of the
death of over 2,500 heads of cattle in the past 46 days.
</P>
<P>
He said that Terra Nuova had sent a message to the region two
months ago that a large vaccination campaign would be launched in
the area and therefore all herds be collected in Hagar and
Qalawaley village for the vaccination.
</P>
<P>
"All of the nomads were notified of the chance and everyone had
brought their cattle to the designated vaccine sites," said
Hassan.
</P>
<P>
"But unfortunately, Terra Nuova did not show up and day after
day, week after week, the cows had begun dying in dozens for lack
of grazing and water accompanied by killer diseases," he added.
</P>
<P>
In finding a solution to the problem, Hassan said his men had
held a meeting and made the decision that Terra Nuova should pay
100,000 U.S. dollars for the safe release of the Italian aid
worker and the Somali officer of Hagar town.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman explained that 60,000 U.S. dollars will be for
the compensation of the dead cattle while the other 40,000 dollars
is a fine for the grave mistake Terra Nuova had committed against
what he called the impoverished innocent nomads.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen said the Terra Nuova office in Nairobi and elders
from the region had contacted them over the release of the men.
However, some misunderstanding had occurred which had further
complicated the situation after self-proclaimed delegates had
given out false information about their attitude regarding the
hostage taking.
</P>
<P>
The local elders said there's now quite a few chances in which
they can intervene into the situation.
</P>
<P>
The kidnapped Italian Sotgia told this reporter through the VHF
radio in Hagar Saturday afternoon that he is " so far being
treated well, being fed well and given enough water in a house. "
</P>
<P>
Sotgia said, with very serious and cautious voice, "I have no
medicine, but I am doing fine."
</P>
<P>
The Italian aid worker asked his organization, Terra Nuova, to
accelerate their efforts in securing his safe release.
</P>
<P>
"I just want my organization to find a solution to this
problem quickly, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Abshir Abdullahi Hassan, head of the Terra Nuova office in
Hagar, is also being kept as a hostage in the same place with his
superior, Dr Stefano Sotgia. Abshir is also being blamed for his
role in spreading false information about the expected activities
of Terra Nuova. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: European States, U.S. Remain Different on Future NATO Concept </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The United States and its major
European allies in the 19-nation NATO, which also includes France,
remain divided on NATO's strategic concept for the future.
</P>
<P>
In addition to discussing the crisis in Yugoslavia, the NATO
Washington summit, which started on Friday and is being held in
Washington D.C., the U.S. capital, is dedicated to amending the
alliance's strategic concept for the next century.
</P>
<P>
At the insistence of France, NATO will reportedly keep the
spirit of its 1991 strategic concept, which stipulates that any
NATO action should be in conformity with the principles of the U.N.
Charter.
</P>
<P>
There are many signs to indicate that the United States and its
European allies differ in varying degrees on the strategic concept
of the U.S.-led Western military alliance.
</P>
<P>
The United States seemingly wants to turn NATO into a powerful
tool for safeguarding its global interests, but European countries
wish to insure more independent decision-making powers within NATO,
and to give it a "European identity of defense and security."
</P>
<P>
France and some other Western European countries are opposed to
turning NATO into a "world policeman" and into a "holy alliance"
entitled to act anywhere and everywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
If NATO becomes a world policeman, the United States would be
able to stage military operations anywhere with the support of its
strong military power and presence.
</P>
<P>
It will undoubtedly serve the interests of Washington to be
able to impose its policy of power over others since it is the
only remaining superpower to emerge following the end of the Cold
War era.
</P>
<P>
Although Europe shares the same values and common strategic
interests to a great extent with the United States, it is also
interested in seeing the world move toward a multipolarity instead
of a single polar, structure.
</P>
<P>
With the construction of European integrity, marked by the
birth of the single currency euro, Europe sees the need to develop
a stronger political and military identity.
</P>
<P>
The difference between European countries and the United States
is observable through NATO's on-going war against Yugoslavia. The
United States is using Yugoslavia to test its plan to turn NATO
into a global policeman with few or no restrictions or limitations,
including the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Although France and other European countries are following the
U.S. lead in the war against Yugoslavia, they regard NATO's action
as a strict exception to the rules of international relations.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting of the NATO ambassadors council in Brussels this
week, European countries expressed their opposition to an
abdication of the prerogatives of the United Nations Security
Council over NATO.
</P>
<P>
Before going to Washington to attend the NATO summit, which is
also marking the 50th anniversary of its founding, French
President Jacques Chirac called for an "acceleration of the
establishment of a European defense."
</P>
<P>
He said the Washington summit should be a new step toward the
building of a European defense, rather than a step back.
</P>
<P>
Even Britain, the closest ally of the U.S. in Europe, expressed
its support to the idea of building a European defense system at
the Franco-British summit last year in Saint Malo.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said recently that Europe
needs to speak with one voice and to establish its own decision-
making mechanism on security.
</P>
<P>
The differences existing between the allies on both sides of
the Atlantic over the future of NATO will surely exert a major
impact on the evolution of relations between the two sides in the
future, as well as the evolution of NATO itself. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
