<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Doctors to Be Guided by New Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A new law is to be introduced in
China on May 1 this year to regulate the licensing of doctors in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Over 100 scholars and doctors today discussed the enforcement
of the law at a seminar organized by the NPC Education, Science
Culture and Health Committee.
</P>
<P>
The law was approved by the Third Meeting of the 9th Chinese
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee on June 26,
1998, and was promulgated through President Jiang Zemin's No.5
presidential decree.
</P>
<P>
China now has over 1.5 million doctors and 463,000
practitioners with secondary medical school education in over 300,
000 medical organizations throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Delegates said that the implementation of the law will provide
a legal framework within which doctors can work, guarantee their
rights and develop China's medical system.
</P>
<P>
Peng Peiyun, vice-chairwoman of the National People's Congress
Standing Committee, said that local governments and people's
congresses at all levels should closely adhere to this law.
</P>
<P>
National People's Congress Standing Committee vice-chairmen Wu
Jieping and He Luli, and Health Minister Zhang Wenkang attended
the seminar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Change to Scholarships Policy in S'pore: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong Saturday ruled out the replacement of scholarships with
loans for students, saying his cabinet had agreed not to make any
change to the policy of scholarships.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launch ceremony of Singapore 21, a vision for
Singapore in the 21st century, Goh said he did not "favor the
replacement of scholarships with loans for our brighter students."
</P>
<P>
"The government will continue to give only scholarships for
courses of study in areas where the state thinks it needs talent
and expertise," Goh said. His remarks drew applause from
participants.
</P>
<P>
"Many parents and students would no doubt find tuition loans
attractive as they give students the freedom to decide on their
choice of university course," he said. "But the government should
not use public funds for an individual's self-fulfillment. They
should be used for national interests."
</P>
<P>
His comment came just days after Deputy Prime Minister and
Defense Minister Tony Tan made a suggestion that Singapore should
seriously consider scrapping government scholarships.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to the United States last week, Tan suggested
study loans should replace scholarships with exceptions in the
Armed Forces and Administrative Services.
</P>
<P>
Tan reportedly said scholarships were "silly" because they
force employers to hold positions for scholars, who may not like
to join them after their studies or who may not turn out to be the
best people for the job.
</P>
<P>
Referring to loan funds, Tan said students can borrow funds to
go abroad to study and the arrangement allows both employers and
scholars to make a decision after a long course of study.
</P>
<P>
In his speech Saturday, Prime Minister Goh said Singapore 21, a
final report developed by the Singapore 21 Committee after
consultations with thousands of Singaporeans at different levels,
represents the ideas and views about the kind of future society
many Singaporeans want for themselves.
</P>
<P>
Singapore 21 identifies five apparent dilemmas or future
challenges Singaporeans will have to resolve, and also five key
ideas to resolve the dilemmas.
</P>
<P>
Goh said Singapore 21 is about forging new partnerships in
society. "The public sector creates conditions for the growth and
development of Singapore while the private sector creates wealth
for the country."
</P>
<P>
"In addition," he said, "there is the people sector, made up of
all the social, community and voluntary groups."
</P>
<P>
"This sector provides the avenues for Singaporeans to
contribute to bringing about the kind of Singapore they wish to
have for themselves and their children," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In the new millennium, we need a strong public sector, a
vibrant private sector and a dynamic people sector working
together to secure the future of Singapore," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
