<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Envoy Repeats Claim Over Yugoslav Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Balkans envoy Viktor
Chernomyrdin repeated Saturday Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic's statement that he had agreed to "the deployment in
Kosovo of an international force with extensive participation of
Russia."
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said the West doesn't understand what had been
discussed during his trip to Belgrade on Thursday and shouldn't be
so quick to dismiss the latest proposal.
</P>
<P>
Western leaders "don't know what Milosevic and I agreed upon.
When I meet with them, I will inform them and explain (Milosevic's)
position. And only then will we talk about their reaction," the
former Russian prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
But he sidestepped questions about a claim he made that
Milosevic had agreed to a military force.
</P>
<P>
"There's nothing to add or change what I said yesterday,"
Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
Those allegations have been denied by Yugoslavia. Yugoslav
Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic said Chernomyrdin and Milosevic
hadn't even talked about the possibility of an international
military presence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Valentin Sergeyev, a Chernomyrdin aide, said
Chernomyrdin hadn't been talking about an armed military force but
only about "people dressed in military uniforms" as part of an
otherwise civilian mission.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin's peace plan was also dismissed by western leaders
because it didn't mention the full withdrawal of Yugoslav forces
from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The former prime minister, who was appointed special Balkans
envoy earlier this month, ruled out Russia's military involvement
in the Yugoslav crisis and said he wanted to discuss with Western
leaders ways of ending the violence.
</P>
<P>
"There is no need to frighten people with warships. There is a
danger that we might slide into a third world war, and that would
be the last war," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Russia will convince the two sides to come to a peaceful
solution. Yugoslavia has already made compromises. Now I shall
talk with NATO."
</P>
<P>
Russia sent a reconnaissance ship to the Adriatic to monitor
the Yugoslav crisis, but President Boris Yeltsin has made clear he
will not be pushed into armed confrontation with the West.
</P>
<P>
"Of course, there must be wide autonomy for Kosovo, and
President Milosevic has also agreed with this. This is very
important," Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
"The main thing now is to organize the negotiating process
between the Yugoslav side and the ethnic Albanian leaders."
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said Russia had a key role to play as mediator
between Yugoslavia, ethnic Albanians and NATO.
</P>
<P>
He said he was ready to fly to Washington, Bonn and other
Western capitals in the coming days to brief the leaders of NATO
countries on his talks with Milosevic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
