<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boom in Ashes Scattering on the Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Traditional funerals where
bodies are buried are becoming a thing of the past in China as
more and more people opt for scattering the ashes of their loved
ones in the sea.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the Beijing Civil Affairs Bureau said that
increasing numbers of Beijingers are requesting permissions for
the sea-board farewell to the dead even years after they died.
</P>
<P>
For example, 83-year-old Wang Ruikun today scattered the ashes
of his wife who died three years ago and those of his second son
who passed away six year ago into the Bohai Sea just off Tianjin,
north China's largest port city.
</P>
<P>
Surrounded by his first son and granddaughter and other
relatives, the short frail man said without hesitation: "I've
decided to have my ashes treated this way, too."
</P>
<P>
Along with Wang today were also 237 Beijing residents, who made
the three-hour journey to the sea to participate in a collective
ashes-scattering ceremony. And thus it was that the ashes of 92
souls were cast into the sea accompanied by flower petals in the
ceremony, which took about an hour.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the bureau approved the scattering of the ashes of
529 souls into the Bohai Sea, up 53 percent over 1997. Every year
over 70,000 people die in the Chinese capital of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"Anticipating further growth in the demand for this new trend,
the bureau plans to organise at least six collective ashes-
scattering trips this year," said Zhang Wanxing, head of the
bureau's funeral and internment section.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the bureau has organized 15 similar
events involving the ashes of 2,113 dead people.
</P>
<P>
The bureau conducts the sea trips purely for the benefit of
society and only charges each person traveling for transportation
and a lunch plus a token fee of 300 yuan (around 36 US dollars).
If no relatives are available to scatter the ashes, the bureau
clerks will do it under the jurisdiction of the notary office, for
a charge of 100 yuan.
</P>
<P>
However, the bureau is not the first to jump on this trendy
funeral bandwagon, for the privately-owned Beijing Peaceful Soul
Service Company started the craze with the city's first ashes-
scattering event in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Peaceful Soul commissioned Chinese composer Wang Xilin to
write a "Requiem" musical piece with Chinese characteristics.
Apart from inviting professional orchestras to play the music, the
company's elaborate ceremonies also include strewing the "
homeland's soil and water", letting pigeons loose in the sky and
burning firecrackers.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the fees for transportation and a meal, the
company charges 1,000 yuan for each customer. However, because it
is hidden away at a corner of the Zhongshan Park at the west side
of the Tiananmen Rostrum, the company has failed to attract enough
customers to be profitable. It has been kept afloat by the 50-year-
old boss Zhang Kai's money-spinning efforts which include a
dismantling, packaging and transport business.
</P>
<P>
Bao Yuan, an expert on funerals and internment from the
Ministry of Civil Affairs, said that major coastal cities from
Guangzhou in the south to Dalian and Dandong in the north are also
leading torch-bearers in the emerging new custom.
</P>
<P>
He said that putting one's ashes in the trust of the sea is
actually the second revolution in China's history of funerals and
interment.
</P>
<P>
The first revolution broke out in 1956, when Mao Zedong and 150
other central and provincial government officials agreed to be
cremated, according to the expert.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the cremation rate in China is 39 percent with
Beijing's rate being a massive 98 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
