<HEADLINE> Bomb Explodes Near U.S., British Consulates in Russian City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A bomb exploded Saturday outside a
building housing the U.S. and British consulates in Yekaterinburg,
causing no casualties.
</P>
<P>
The blast, which occurred at about 6 a.m. (0000GMT), blew out
windows in the surrounding buildings, the local media reported.
</P>
<P>
The bomb was placed in a bag under a car parked 10 meters from
the consulates, media reports said.
</P>
<P>
Police did not know if the explosion in Yekaterinburg -- about
1,500 kilometers east of Moscow -- was connected to U.S. and
British involvement in NATO airstrikes in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Anti-western sentiment has been on the rise around Russia since
NATO started airstrikes against Yugoslavia on March 24.
Demonstrations were held outside the U.S. embassy in central
Moscow in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
Three weeks ago, a gunman fired at the U.S. embassy in protest
against the air raids on Yugoslavia, but no one was injured.
</P>
</TEXT>
