<HEADLINE> French Troops Begin Re-Deployment South of Tirana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- French troops stationed in the
airport of the Albanian capital Tirana began to re-deploy toward
the south on Saturday in preparation for NATO's "Allied Shelter"
humanitarian mission for Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted officers of the French Army
in Albania as saying that the first group of about 50 French
soldiers had moved to Elbasan, 55 kilometers south of Tirana,
where the base of the Task Force South is located, one of the four
NATO contingents for "Allied Shelter."
</P>
<P>
France has already sent 300 soldiers to the airport of Rinas in
Tirana over the past few week, and will send 450 soldiers to
reinforce the "Allied Shelter" mission next week.
</P>
<P>
Some French tanks will also arrive next Tuesday at the port of
Durres, southern Albania, said the AFP.
</P>
<P>
Task Force South is under the commander of France and will have
a total of 1,300 soldiers from France, Denmark, Greece and the
United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
NATO said that the "Allied Shelter" will have two other bases --
one in northern Albania, and another in the Durres region, to
serve as a transit point for NATO soldiers and equipment.
</P>
<P>
A total of 7,000 NATO soldiers are participating in the "Allied
Shelter" operation. 
</P>
