<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Shed Loss-Making Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China's largest industrial city
of Shanghai is determined to reduce by 15 percent the number of
big and medium-sized loss-making enterprises by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
 At present, about 35 percent of the state-owned or state-
holding companies in the city are in the red, according to the
municipal government.
</P>
<P>
 Once the 15 percent target is realized, about 400 enterprises
would free themselves from the current difficulties.
</P>
<P>
 To provide a better external environment for the enterprises,
the government has set up a special unit to coordinate policies
and the allocation of resources.
</P>
<P>
 Shanghai has every confidence it can meet this target, a city
official said, and there has appeared a favorable deficit-cutting
trend in the city since last year.
</P>
<P>
 In the first two months of the year, the city's industrial
enterprises recorded 2.2 billion yuan (260 million U.S. dollars)
profit, up 31.3 percent over the same period of last year, the
official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
