<HEADLINE> Iran Urges Political Solution to Afghan Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry
Spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi on Saturday called for an end to the
fighting in Afghanistan and for a political solution to the
Afghan crisis.
</P>
<P>
Asefi voiced Tehran's concerns over the escalation of conflicts
in Afghanistan and expressed regret that the Afghan Taliban
militia refused to continue peace talks with the opposition
Northern Alliance, led by the ousted Afghan President Burhanuddin
Rabbani, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored Afghan peace talks were held in Ashkhabad,
Turkmenistan in February and March, but the Taliban did not take
part in the follow-up negotiations on April 12.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said that Taliban militia clashed with
the Northern Alliance in the past week in the Bamian region, the
main center for the Afghan Shiite Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Resorting to force and refusing to hold peace talks will bring
nothing, the Iranian spokesman said, stressing the need for
resumption of peace talks between the Afghan groups to form a
broad-based government in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Voicing support for efforts of the United Nations to bring
peace to Afghanistan, he also highlighted the need to implement
the resolutions of the U.N. Security Council, the U.N. General
Assembly and the "6 plus 2" formed by Afghanistan's six neighbors
as well as Russia and the U.S..
</P>
<P>
The resolutions called for peaceful settlement of the Afghan
civil war and the establishment of a broad-based government in
Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
