<HEADLINE> Italian Aid Worker Kidnapped in Somalia "Treated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Italian veterinarian aid
worker, Dr Stefano Sotgia kidnapped by Somali gunmen in the town
of Hagar a week ago, said he is "so far being treated well," and
urged for a quick release.
</P>
<P>
Sotgia told this reporter through the VHF radio in Hagar 165
kilometers northwest of the southern port city of Kismayu this
afternoon that he is " so far being treated well, being fed well
and given enough water in a house. "
</P>
<P>
Sotgia said, with very serious and cautious voice, "I have no
medicine, but I am doing fine."
</P>
<P>
The Italian aid worker asked his organization, Terra Nuova, to
accelerate their efforts in securing his safe release.
</P>
<P>
"I just want my organization to find a solution to this
problem quickly, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Abshir Abdullahi Hassan, head of the Terra Nuova office in
Hagar, is also being kept as a hostage in the same place with his
superior, Dr Stefano Sotgia. Abshir is also being blamed for his
role in spreading false information about the expected activities
of Terra Nuova.
</P>
<P>
Marwas Yareh Hassan, spokesman for the gunmen holding the Terra
Nuova staff members has threatened, on VHF radio contact with this
reporter, that they will take an emergency decision unless
something quick is done in the next 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman has refused to elaborate what kind of
decision they are likely to take. Speculations are that they may
loose patience in the treatment of their captives. 
</P>
