<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Minister Facing Impeachment Defies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Despite the impeachment threat
against him, Iran's moderate Minister of Culture and Islamic
Guidance Ataollah Mohajerani vowed to continue his open-minded
policies on press and cultural affairs.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here Saturday, Mohajerani said
his ministry's policies would not change, even if he would be
removed by the impeachment motion of conservative Majlis
(parliament).
</P>
<P>
He noted that all the policies in his ministry have been
confirmed by President Mohammad Khatami and he would not change
the policies under impeachment pressures.
</P>
<P>
"We observed no changes in the Interior Ministry after former
Interior Minister (Abdollah Nouri) was impeached by the Majlis
(last June)," said Mohajerani, also spokesman of Khatami's
government.
</P>
<P>
A group of 31 conservative Majlis deputies on Wednesday tabled
a motion against Mohajerani, accusing him of failing to uphold
Islamic and revolutionary values by adopting a liberal policy on
the press, book publishing and the arts.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers also charged him of misappropriating public funds
for minor Hajj rituals.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani immediately announced his readiness to attend the
Majlis session to face an impeachment trial. The Majlis decided to
debate the motion next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani told reporters said that the impeachment has long
been planned. "Some Majlis deputies called for impeachment against
me even one month after I received a vote of confidence from the
Majlis to be the minister of culture and Islamic guidance in
1997," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister termed the impeachment motion as "a factional
political move" against the moderates. "The impeachment has been
on the table, it only needs some pretexts," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the motion was aimed at a major change in the
ministry and its policy.
</P>
<P>
The minister, a close ally and strong supporter of Khatami,
underlined that the motion against him would fail and he would
succeed in gaining a vote of confidence from the Majlis.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani is the second minister of Khatami's cabinet
targeted by the powerful conservatives, who still dominate the
country's most important organs, such as the judiciary, the
Majlis and armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Since former Interior Minister Abdollah Nouri was sacked by the
Majlis, Mohajerani has come under fire. The conservatives vowed to
elbow the moderates or Khatami's supporters out of the Iranian
political arena.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with local daily Iran News published on
Thursday, Mohajerani said the impeachment motion against him was
politically motivated and would backfire. "Experience has shown
that such moves will backfire and only add to the popularity of
the person put under pressure," he said.
</P>
<P>
Khatami named Nouri as vice president as after he was impeached
in a move of defiance.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani vowed to continue his political activities "with
better planning" even if the impeachment succeeds in removing him
from office.
</P>
<P>
"I may run as a candidate in the sixth Majlis elections (next
year), I am not the type of person to buckle under pressure and I
will continue to fulfill my political and social duties," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
