<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donors Pledge to Continue Aid to Bangladesh: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's donors have pledged to
continue assistance to the country's economic development, Finance
Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the donor community discussed with the
Bangladeshi delegation the situation in the country, including
such issues as the opposition's role and hartals, at the two-day
Bangladesh Development Forum in Paris on Monday and Tuesday,
Kibria told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
"What the donors desired is development in Bangladesh," he
said, adding that there was no difference between the aims of the
donors and the Bangladeshi government.
</P>
<P>
On donors' aid pledge to Bangladesh, the minister said the
"donors found the country's projection is realistic," shunning a
direct answer whether they had made any definitive commitments of
aid this year.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh was seeking 2.04 billion U.S. dollars from the
donors at the forum, previously known as the Bangladesh Aid Group
Meeting.
</P>
<P>
The donors' aid flow would be more in the next fiscal
(beginning July 1, 1999) than the amount sought at the Paris
meeting if utilization could be increased and on-going financial
reforms accelerated, according to the finance minister.
</P>
<P>
The donors, "not fully happy" over the pace of reforms,
suggested accelerating the reforms, particularly in the banking
and financial sectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
At a video press conference on Tuesday, Kibria told reporters
from Paris that he had received "general assurance" from the
donors about continuing the normal flow of assistance. "We have
requested for certain amount of assistance... we have received
general assurance," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, which had earlier said that there would be "no
pledging session" this year, said in a statement that "the
development partners noted that the (Bangladeshi) government has
projected new aid commitments of 2.04 billion dollars for fiscal
year 2000" and "this projection is realistic in the context of
accelerated reforms." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
