<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Says Religious Group Responsible for Aborted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iranian official said
Saturday that a new Iranian religious group called "Mahdaviyat"
was responsible for the assassination attempt against an Iranian
judicial official in January.
</P>
<P>
Brigadier General Mohammad Ali Jaafari, commander of the ground
forces of the Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC), said that
the leader and some of the members of the group had been arrested,
the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Jaafari made the remark after some Iranian newspapers claimed
that the IRGC was behind the failed assassination against head of
Tehran Justice Department Ali Razini, who was wounded in the leg,
abdomen and chest by a bomb attached to his car.
</P>
<P>
The IRGC commander said that a member of the group, who had
served in a bomb defusing squad during the Iran-Iraq war
(1980-88), made the remote-control bomb.
</P>
<P>
He said that the 30-member group had intellectual links with a
clergyman named only as Milani, the grandson of Ayatollah Seyed
Mohammad Hadi Milani, a prominent Iranian religious leader who
died before the Islamic revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
However, Jaafari said that the group had no connection with
the recent assassination of Brigadier General Ali Sayyad Shirazi,
deputy chief of the Joint Staff of the Iranian armed forces, who
was shot dead in front of his house earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Jaafari said the military had also confiscated 100 guns stolen
by the group.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that no member of the group is associated with any
military or security agency and that one of them had been
officially recruited by IRGC, but was later expelled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
