<HEADLINE> Chinese Mayors Discuss Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to realize China's
trans-century economic and social goals, people should pay close
attention to the relationship between population, resources and
the environment, officials from Chinese major cities said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Mayors and leaders from the Ministry of Construction and nine
Chinese cities including Beijing, Tianjin and Chongqing attended
today's conference on people and the environment.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang, once listed by the WHO (World Health Organization) as
one of the world's ten most severely polluted cities, has taken
great efforts to curb urban environment pollution in recent years.
The city stepped out of the "Black List" in 1998, and became one
of China's cleanest cities.
</P>
<P>
Officials from Shenyang city government told delegates that its
achievements in curbing air pollution, treating urban sewage and
city garbage were to be admired.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang will spend 25 billion yuan in 50 major urban
construction projects in the coming two years, including three
sewage treatment plants. The city aims to be able to handle all
urban garbage by 2000. 
</P>
