<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xiamen Plays Bigger Role in Shipping with Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Southeast China's port of Xiamen
is playing a bigger role in direct shipping between the mainland
and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
 Statistics showed that the port handled 187,374 containers in
the first quarter of this year, up 20.8 percent over the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
 Direct shipments to Taiwan amounted to 74,290 containers, up
62.03 percent over the first quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
 Owing to restrictions imposed by Taiwan, there has been no
direct shipping links between the two sides of the Taiwan Straits
for decades.
</P>
<P>
 In April, 1997, a pilot program for direct shipping was
introduced. By the end of March this year, there had been 2,239
direct shipments between the two sides, involving a total of 345,
000 containers.
</P>
<P>
 Thanks to its proximity to Taiwan, the port has had a bigger
part to play in the new shipping schedules with the island.
</P>
<P>
 Xiamen's direct shipments to Taiwan involved 75.99 percent of
the total shipments of the mainland to Taiwan in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
