<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Reaffirms Compliance with OPEC Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has reaffirmed its full
compliance with OPEC (Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries) production cuts and promised to decrease148,000 barrels
per day (bpd), bringing its daily output to 1,885,000 barrels.
</P>
<P>
National Planning Minister Chief Rasheed Gbadamosi said Friday
in capital Abuja that the Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation
has already directed local oil producing firms to cut their daily
output by five to seven percent, the Guardian newspapers reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The production cuts was agreed by OPEC members at its 107th
meeting in Vienna last March, explained the minister who led
Nigeria's delegation to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
As the oil price at international markets rose to 16.50 U.S.
Dollars per barrel on Friday, the Nigerian minister predicted that
it is feasible the price go up to 18-19 Dollars at the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, an OPEC member and the sixth largest oil exporting
country in the world, is expected to reap a windfall from crude
oil sale as the government based this year's budget on the average
price of nine Dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Gbadamosi told reporters that "indeed, the average selling
price has now hit 15 Dollars per barrel and by the end of this
year, the prospects for 18- 19 Dollars look feasible."
</P>
<P>
Given the prospect from the rising crude oil price, he noted,
this year' s budget will have to be re-engineered to reflect the
new development with more proceeds going into deficit financing of
the budget.
</P>
<P>
The minister pointed out "if we are able to hold our finances
and control deficit, we will be able to get debt rescheduling from
creditors."
</P>
<P>
"Once the macro economic stability remains stable, we will get
core investors and the economy will expand," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
