<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News analysis: Indian Politicians Face Hard Choices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Indian politicians now face
hard choices concerning government formation following failure of
the largest opposition party, the Congress, to get support of at
least 272 members of parliament out of the total number of 543.
</P>
<P>
The Congress's bid to form a minority government with outside
support of other opposition parties was virtually derailed Friday
when Samajawadi (socialist) Party (SP), which has 20 seats in Lok
Sabha (lower house of parliament), announced its opposition to a
Congress-led government.
</P>
<P>
Another two parties of the opposition camp, Revolutionary
Socialist Party (RSP) and All Indian Forward Block (AIFB), which
together have 7 seats in Lok Sabha, also rejected the idea of a
Congress-led government.
</P>
<P>
Congress leader Sonia Gandhi met President Kocheril Raman
Narayanan Friday, the second time in two days, and handed over a
list of only 233 members of parliament who have pledged support
for her party, 39 short of the least margin of majority in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, the president asked her to continue consultations with
other parties and try to form an alternative government, saying he
would not take a "hasty decision" on government formation.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued late Friday night from the presidential
palace said that the president would take into account past
precedents as well as "new circumstances, some of which are
altogether without earlier paradigms in India."
</P>
<P>
The current political crisis arose on Saturday last week when
the coalition government led by the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP)
was voted down in Lok Sabha.
</P>
<P>
Before and after the fall of the BJP-led government, Sonia
Gandhi insisted on formation of a Congress-led government with
outside support of other parties in the opposition camp and she
had promised two days ago when she met the president to produce a
list of 272 MPs backing her party.
</P>
<P>
With refusal of support by SP, RSP and AIFB, the Congress can
not manage to get the least majority of 272 in parliament and the
choices facing the biggest opposition is either to agree to a
coalition with, possibly, a prime minister from other party, or a
mid-term election which both the BJP and its allies and most
parties in the opposition have tried to avoid.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the BJP has managed to gather support of some 270
MPs and claimed the right of reinstallation of the coalition ever
since its fall a week ago.
</P>
<P>
What has been agreed among the opposition is to prevent the
reinstallation of the BJP government with Atal Behari Vajpayee as
its prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Following the announcement by SP, RSP and AIFB, Congress
leaders indicated that a coalition government could not be ruled
out, but the shape of a future government has not been decided.
</P>
<P>
For smaller opposition parties, each has its own interests to
consider, pulling down the Vajpayee government is one thing,
formatting a new one is another.
</P>
<P>
The ball is now in the court of the president, who has been
reportedly seriously considering various options to install "a
viable and stable government" including the hardest choice of
bring back Vajpayee as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Narayanan, too, would be averse to a mid-term poll, according
to Lok Sabha speaker G. M. C. Galayogi, who met the president
Friday.
</P>
<P>
For several days, Narayanan has been busy meeting various party
and state leaders to solicit their views on government formation.
</P>
<P>
Some who met the president on Friday left with the impression
that Narayanan would prefer to go through the motion of inviting
the so-called third front leaders, who belong to parties with a
number of members of parliament, to form a government after Sonia
Gandhi reported success or failure in her efforts.
</P>
<P>
Another choice for Indian politicians is to kick the ball to
parliament and let it decide the formation of a government or the
fate of the Congress, BJP and others.
</P>
<P>
Any way, what Indians and most of the political parties want to
see is a quick solution to the political crisis and a future
government which is stable and efficient as the unstable political
environment has already brought adverse effects to their daily
life socially and economically. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
