<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for U.N. Intervention in Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi called for intervention of the United Nations in a
settlement of the Kosovo crisis, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Talking by phone with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Friday
night, Kharrazi praised his initiative on the Balkan crisis and
hoped his forthcoming visit to Russia would pave the way for a
unanimous resolution at the U.N. Security Council on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The conditions for such a resolution are appropriate, he said,
adding that all members of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC) contact group underlined the role of the
U.N. secretary-general and the intervention of the Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi briefed Annan on the results of the OIC contact group
officials' recent shuttle visit to Russia, Albania, Italy and
Germany over the Kosovo issue. The group includes Iran, Malaysia,
Pakistan, Turkey, Morocco, Senegal, Egypt and Saudi Arabia,
</P>
<P>
After returning from the visit, Kharrazi on Friday underlined
the need of an international consensus in settling the Kosovo
crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said that no action should be taken against Yugoslavia
without the consent and approval of the U.N. Security Council and
any action against Yugoslavia without consent would cause
displacement, ethnic cleansing and massacre of the Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
In the phone conservation, Annan underlined the need to find a
diplomatic solution to settle the crisis and the ethnical
cleansing in Kosovo and expressed hope that his visit to Europe
would be successful.
</P>
<P>
In order to prevent further complication of the Balkan crisis,
a diplomatic solution must be found soon, he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan praised the efforts by the OIC contact group regarding
the crisis, which has been worsened by the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization's massive air strikes against Yugoslavia a month
ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
