<HEADLINE> Report Says 3rd NATO Missile Lands on Bulgarian Territory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A NATO air-to-surface missile
landed and exploded near a western Bulgarian village 20 kilometers
away from the border with Yugoslavia late Thursday, the third
since NATO began air strikes a month ago, Bulgarian newspaper
Monitor reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The report, quoting sources with the Defense Ministry, said no
casualties were caused by the explosion, which occurred in Babitsa
village around 07:00 p.m. local time. The nearest civilian
residence was 200-300 meters away.
</P>
<P>
Experts of the Defense Ministry said the missile -- measuring 4.
17 meters in length and 361 kilometers in weight -- had been
launched from air some 25 kilometers away from the border. It was
marked with AGM-88-HARM on the body.
</P>
<P>
On March 26 and 31, wrecks of NATO air-to-air missiles fell on
the Bulgarian territory after exploding in air. 
</P>
