<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Bombings Hit Three Serbian Towns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Powerful bombings hit three
Serbian towns of Nis, Novi Sad and Kraljevo early Saturday as NATO
air strikes against Yugoslavia entered the 32nd day.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia's official Tanjug news agency reported that NATO
aircraft dropped 26 powerful bombs just after midnight on Nis,
some 220 kilometers south of Belgrade, hitting factories, schools
and residential areas and damaging water and electricity supply
facilities.
</P>
<P>
At 2:45 a.m. local time, NATO bombings smashed a fuel depot and
a section of highway in Kraljevo, 150 kilometers south of Belgrade.
Half an hour later, NATO warplanes launched another attack on the
oil refinery in Novi Sad in northern Serbia.
</P>
<P>
In Belgrade, people experienced a relatively quiet night with
no sounds of flying planes, blasts or anti-aircraft fires, except
for sirens at 10:15 p.m. local time Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, several thousand volunteers from Belgrade,
Montenegro, Bosnia, Greece, Macedonia, Ukraine, Russia, Italy and
some Arab countries continued to stand as "human shields" on three
bridges across the Sava and Danube rivers, chanting songs in
protest against NATO's raids on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Reports say that thousands of Belgraders are going to rally at
the central square in the Yugoslav capital at midday Saturday to
mourn for those killed by NATO bombings at the Serbian state radio
and television building early Friday. The Tanjug reported that at
least 10 people were killed and 18 injured in the attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
