<HEADLINE> Warning to Computer Users Against Virus Posted in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A computer emergency response
team at Carnegie Mellon University on Friday posted a warning to
computer users against a malicious computer virus set to strike
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The new virus was called the Chernobyl virus because it is
timed to go off on the anniversary of the Russian nuclear accident,
one of technology's worst disasters.
</P>
<P>
The most common version of the Chernobyl virus, also known as "
CIH", was programmed to activate on computers using Windows 95 and
Windows 98 on Monday, the 13th anniversary of the nuclear disaster
in Ukraine, computer experts said.
</P>
<P>
They added that the Chernobyl virus can erase a computer's hard-
drive and prevent the equipment from restarting.
</P>
<P>
Carey Nachenberg, chief researcher at Symantec's Antivirus
Research Center, said one big risk, that stems from a potential
infection on a company's computer net work, could then spread to
individual computers.
</P>
<P>
"If it gets on a corporate network and the volumes are not
protected, it could spread very, very rapidly," Nachenberg said.
</P>
<P>
The warning could be read on the web site at http://www.cert.
org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
