<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Lifts Ban on Sale of Fish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has lifted
the month-long ban on the sale of fish nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Fisheries Fred Mukisa announced the
decision here Friday that the ban was lifted after verifying that
fish poisoning had substantially reduced in the 10 districts on
the Lake Victoria shores.
</P>
<P>
Local communities, particularly those on Victoria islands, had
been lacking food due to the fish ban, Saturday's New Vision
daily quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
To punish the offenders, local authorities recommended that
anybody caught using poison to catch fish should be imprisoned
according to laws that will be set by local authorities.
</P>
<P>
Mukisa said persons involved in fisheries will have to register
their residences, fishing boats, types of gear and types of fish
they catch. Identity cards are to be issued to this effect.
</P>
<P>
The newly formed fish inspection services are now in place and
committees with powers to set bylaws and to arrest offenders have
been set up, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
The fish ban was imposed a month ago following massive fish
poisoning on Lake Victoria, the world's second largest fresh water
lake. Poisoned fish cost at least four lives in the capital area.
The European Union subsequently also banned fish exports from East
Africa. The ban made Uganda lose some one million dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
