<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: UNICEF to Enhance Cooperation with China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bellamy, who has just completed her China visit at the
invitation of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation (MOFTEC), said that UNICEF is keen to expand mutual
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In a Xinhua interview Friday Bellamy said it seemed to her that
the Chinese government has attached importance to the work of
women and children and achieved most of the goals set out in its
children's development program.
</P>
<P>
She referred to the fact that China has been polio free for
several years, and that the iodine deficiency disease has been
reduced dramatically.
</P>
<P>
"China now has a lot of primary infant hospitals which has
helped reduce the death rate of infants," she added.
</P>
<P>
She praised China's achievements in pushing forward compulsory
education, which enables school-aged children to have the
opportunity to study and described China's Hope Project as "
successful".
</P>
<P>
But she also said that the rate of girl school drop-outs is
still high, and trafficking in women and children still happens
now and then because of China's economic disparity and the
remnants of old traditions.
</P>
