<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 07:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Lebanese Official Indicted on Embezzlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's former Director-General
of Antiquities Camille Asmar and three associates have been
formally charged with embezzlement, the Daily Star reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
State Prosecutor for Financial Fraud Ahmad Taqieddine Friday
filed charges against Asmar and the other suspects after
investigators discovered that the directorate's 3.3 million
U.S. dollars had gone missing during Asmar's tenure.
</P>
<P>
The missing funds are believed to have been squandered through
the payment of forged and fictitious bills.
</P>
<P>
In addition, some 5 million dollars in foreign grants which
the directorate had received before Asmar was fired by the
Cabinet in January have apparently also gone into private pockets,
the paper quoted judicial sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The suspect's files were referred to Beirut Investigative
Magistrate Raymond Oueidat. If convicted, they could face up to
three years' imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Asmar, who served the department for 36 consecutive years that
included the 1975-1990 civil war, became the second highest
ranking Lebanese official to be indicted on a corruption charge
since President Emile Lahoud took office last November.
</P>
<P>
The president vowed to eradicate rampant corruption and take
back all public funds stolen by officials of former government of
Rafik Hariri.
</P>
<P>
The first to be charged was former Oil Minister Shahe
Barsoumian, who faces an embezzlement charge of 800 million
dollars in shady fuel deals during his three-year tenure that
ended last November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
