<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0745 GMT April 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Defense ministers of the 19-member NATO on Friday
authorized allied naval forces in principle to block ships
delivering oil and arms to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
A senior NATO official, who attended the NATO summit here, said
that the ministers authorized NATO naval forces to stop and search
any suspected ships to Yugoslavia. The allied forces, the official
told reporters, will take "all of the measures necessary to
establish the mechanisms for a visit-and-search regime." (NATO-
Yugoslavia-Oil)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia and Belarus will work together to establish a
regional military group from 2001 to 2005 as planned, Russian
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev told a press conference held in
Minsk.
</P>
<P>
The minister was quoted by ITAR-TASS as saying that the
Yugoslavia crisis accelerated the process of decision-making on
military technical cooperation between his country and Belarus.
The two countries are prepared to carry out completely their
bilateral plan for military technical cooperation for 2001-2005,
Sergeyev said. (Russia-Belarus-Military)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivorad Jovanovic on Friday
reiterated the opposition to the deployment of international
forces in Kosovo, according to the ITAR-TASS news agency.
</P>
<P>
Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin and Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic did not talk about the issue of "international
military presence" in Kosovo during their meeting on Wednesday, a
senior Yugoslav diplomat, on behalf of Jovanovic, told the
Belgrade bureau of ITAR-TASS. They just discussed the possibility
of sending civil staff to Kosovo, he said. The diplomat also
expressed his dissatisfaction over some media reports saying that
"Yugoslavia has agreed to the deployment of 'international
presence' under the UN flag and with the participation of Russia."
(Yugoslavia-Kosovo-Foreign Forces)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- NATO leaders signed and issued "The Washington
Declaration" here Friday, reaffirming their commitment to enhanced
collective defense and continued expansion of membership as the
key to achieve "peace and stability" in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
"The world has changed dramatically over the last half century,
but our common values and security interests remain the same,"
said the declaration by the 19 heads of NATO member states who are
attending the current three-day summit beginning here Friday
morning. "We are charting NATO's course as we enter the 21st
century: an Alliance committed to collective defense, capable of
addressing current and future risks to our security, strengthened
by and open to new members and working together with other
institutions, Partners and Mediterranean Dialogue countries in a
mutually reinforcing way to enhance Euro-Atlantic security and
stability," it said. (US-NATO Summit-Washington Declaration)
</P>
</TEXT>
