<HEADLINE> Aid Agencies Pull Out from W. Uganda After Rebel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- International aid agencies have
withdrawn from western Uganda due to increased violence in the
region by Allied Democratic Forces (ADF), a major rebel group
having been active there since 1996.
</P>
<P>
Their pulling out did not mean that they would suspend their
activities there. They were waiting to see how the situation
would develop, Saturday' s Monitor daily quoted U.N. World Food
Program (WFP) country representative in Uganda, Michael Jones, as
saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
The WFP's move came after ADF rebels entered Bundibugyo town
Monday night and began shooting, killing at least two civilians
and wounding an unknown number of others.
</P>
<P>
The rebels were reportedly targeting the Picfare Hotel in the
town, a popular joint for army commanders in the area.
</P>
<P>
Rebel activities have increased since the start of the year and
at least 80 people have died in raids, including 30 killed last
week in attacks on Bundibugyo and the neighboring Kabarole
district.
</P>
<P>
Aid agencies based in Uganda estimated that between 50,000 and
70,000 people there have been displaced by the rebel violence in
the region alone.
</P>
<P>
The ADF rebels currently operate out of camps in the Rwenzori
Mountains straddling the common border with the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC). 
</P>
</TEXT>
