<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Urges Traders to Refrain From Exploiting Oil Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada appealed to businessmen Saturday not to exploit the recent
round of oil price hikes by increasing the prices of their
products and services.
</P>
<P>
The president said Saturday morning in his weekly Radio--TV
program that he has ordered all government agencies concerned to
closely monitor the prices of basic commodities.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that businessmen would not take advantage of this oil
price hike by also raising the prices of their goods," he said.
</P>
<P>
Caltex Philippines, Pilipinas Shell and Petron, the three
biggest oil companies of the country, have raised prices of fuel
products this week by an average of 43 centavos (1.075 cents) to
50 centavos (1.25 cents) per liter.
</P>
<P>
Estrada explained that government is not in a position to stop
the recent round of oil price hikes, because the prices of
petroleum products largely depend on the cost of crude oil in the
world market.
</P>
<P>
The oil industry in the Philippines has also become fully
deregulated, with market forces playing the key role in
determining petroleum prices, he said.
</P>
<P>
The only option available to the government, the president
said, is to have the Energy Regulatory Board monitor oil prices
and make sure the price hikes are reasonable.
</P>
<P>
He said the Department of Justice would file appropriate
charges against firms found making unreasonable price increases.
</P>
<P>
The president said he has ordered Secretary Jose Pardo of the
Department of Trade and Industry to keep tabs on business firms as
well.
</P>
<P>
He said he has also ordered Pardo and Secretary Bienvenido
Laguesma of the Department of Labor and Employment to study a new
package of benefits for workers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said the government
is studying ways to prevent inflation and help workers cope with
current living standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
