<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Summit Issues "Washington Declaration" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- NATO leaders signed and issued
"The Washington Declaration" here Friday, reaffirming their
commitment to enhanced collective defense and continued expansion
of membership as the key to achieve "peace and stability" in the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
"The world has changed dramatically over the last half century,
but our common values and security interests remain the same,"
said the declaration by the 19 heads of NATO member states who are
attending the current three-day summit beginning here Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
"We are charting NATO's course as we enter the 21st century: an
Alliance committed to collective defense, capable of addressing
current and future risks to our security, strengthened by and open
to new members and working together with other institutions,
Partners and Mediterranean Dialogue countries in a mutually
reinforcing way to enhance Euro-Atlantic security and stability,"
it said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that collective defense remains "the core purpose of
NATO," the document stressed the need for "political solidarity"
and strengthened military forces among NATO members so as to meet
the security challenges in the next century.
</P>
<P>
"We pledge to improve our defense capabilities to fulfill the
full range of the Alliance's 21st century missions. We will
continue to build confidence and security through arms control,
disarmament and non-proliferation measures. We reiterate our
condemnation of terrorism and our determination to protect
ourselves against this scourge," it added.
</P>
<P>
The declaration said NATO would keep open to all European
nations, regardless of their geographical locations, so long as
they were willing and able to meet the responsibility of
membership.
</P>
<P>
"NATO is an essential pillar of a wider community of shared
values and shared responsibility," it said.
</P>
<P>
The document also called for the reinforcement of trans-
Atlantic relations in NATO. The destinies of North America and
Europe remain inseparable, it said, adding that "when we act
together, we safeguard our freedom and security and enhance
stability more effectively than any of us could alone."
</P>
<P>
NATO, which has kept pummeling Yugoslavia with air bombs and
cruise missiles in the past month, said in the declaration that it
wants to "live in peace with all nations, and settle any
international dispute by peaceful means." Those high-flight words
have been seen by some media here as "tongue in cheek," showing
nothing but hypocrisy on the part of the Atlantic Alliance.
</P>
<P>
The NATO leaders, who gathered here at the Reagan International
Trade Center Friday afternoon to celebrate the 50th anniversary of
the Alliance, made brief speeches one by one before signing the
declaration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
