<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Migration Increasing Fast in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Urban migration in Bangladesh has
been increasing at a faster rate than ever before due to swelling
landlessness and poor avenues of employment in the rural areas, an
English daily newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 1.2 million households are located in the
urban slums comprising 24 percent of the total urban population of
over 25 million in the country, and of the total slum dwellers,
more than 0.6 million families are either squatters or homeless,
the Bangladesh Observer quoted a survey recently conducted by the
Center for Urban Studies (CUS) as saying.
</P>
<P>
The picture of slums in the capital city Dhaka is alarming, and
now there are 3,007 slums in Dhaka with 220,920 slum dwelling
households, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
Of these slums in Dhaka, 2,328 are located on private lands
while 679 on government lands, and the density of slum population
in the city is 1,065 person per acre, it stated, adding that the
number of slum dwellers in Dhaka is estimated at around 1.5
million.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of landless households in this South Asian
country increased to 28.3 percent in 1998 from 24.1 percent in
1997, according to the recently published Urban Poverty Monitoring
Survey conducted by the Bangladesh Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Presently, the number of Bangladesh's completely landless
households is 2.10 million which was only 1.2 million in 1984 in
the rural areas, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
According to a study of the United Nations Development Program,
there will be accelerated migration of rural people to the capital
city from the year 2015 when the city population will stand at
19.5 million surpassing the population of other mega-cities like
New York, Calcutta and Karachi.
</P>
<P>
Fifty percent of the migrants have been coming to Dhaka from
the rural areas as they were rendered completely landless by river
erosion and frequent floods while the rest for new job
opportunities, said Rita Afsar, a researcher at the Bangladesh
Institute of Development Studies.
</P>
<P>
Natural disasters like drought, floods and river bank erosion
have been endangering the existence of people in the rural areas
and forcing the landless people to migrate to the urban areas as
their last means for survival, explained Anu Muhammed, associate
professor of economics of Jahangirnagar University. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
