<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Major Millers Close Down as Maize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Most major milling companies in
Zimbabwe were closed Friday because of lack of maize supply.
</P>
<P>
Kumbirayi Katsande, president of the Confederation of Zimbabwe
Industries, confirmed the closures Friday, the daily Herald
reported.
</P>
<P>
"For the past three weeks, supplies of raw maize to milling
companies in the country have been well below the level required
to maintain maize meal products in free supply in the market,"
Katsande said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He said the Grain Marketing Board had indicated that supplies
were in transit and production could resume this weekend, provided
the supplies reached the millers soon.
</P>
<P>
He said the industry was concerned that there was confusion in
the country regarding the price at which maize meal products were
being traded.
</P>
<P>
"We want to confirm that there has been no change to the
controlled wholesale and retail maize meal prices that apply in
the market or in the price at which the marketing board is
committed to supplying the industry with maize," he said.
</P>
<P>
The board has increased the price of maize by 63 percent
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
There were fears that millers could increase the price of maize
meal or shut down their operations.
</P>
<P>
However, the price was reduced following government
intervention.
</P>
<P>
Because of the controlled price situation, the Grain Marketing
Board was expected to remain the only supplier of raw maize to the
millers who were in no position to buy maize for the production of
maize meal from other sources at higher prices, Katsande said.
</P>
</TEXT>
