<HEADLINE> UN Willing to Resume Humanitarian Aid to Angolan Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Humanitarian
Assistance Coordination (UNHAC) said here Friday that it is
willing to resume humanitarian assistance to the Angolan refugees
as long as the Angolan government can provide necessary security.
</P>
<P>
Francesco Stripolli, coordinator of the UNHAC, said this as he
was meeting with Angolan Vice Minister of Foreign Affairs Toko
Serao.
</P>
<P>
Stripolli noted that "it is very necessary to add emergency
humanitarian assistance to the provinces of Malanje, Bie and
Huambo." But he pointed out that security is not guaranteed
there.
</P>
<P>
Because the routes leading to these provinces have been cut off
by the rebel troops of the National Union for the Independence of
Angola (UNITA) and most of the airports are within the range of
the UNITA fire, the UNHAC was forced to suspend its relief flights
to the Angolan refugees.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official said that the humanitarian assistance would
be resumed at any time as long as the Angolan government can
guarantee security of the relief actions.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest statistics released by the World Food
Program, the total number of the Angolan refugees has amounted to
1.7 million and the humanitarian situation in the southern African
country is "serious".
</P>
<P>
Local government officials in Angola said recently that the
150,000 refugees besieged in central town of Kuito, capital of Bie
Province, are living in dire conditions and some of them are dying
from hunger or diseases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
