<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (49) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) - Following is part 49 of a question
and answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
Will the Macao Special Administrative Region introduce a
compulsory education system?
</P>
<P>
Compulsory education is an important criterion in determining
the level of educational development of a country or a region.
</P>
<P>
According to the provisions of the General Law of the
Educational System of Macao promulgated in 1991, the Portuguese
Macao Government should provide free education for children at the
government-run and privately sponsored pre-school centers, primary
and junior middle schools.
</P>
<P>
They are exempt from tuition fees or any other fees related to
enrollment, education or certificates. Pupils from the non-
sponsored private schools are entitled to subsidies for tuition
fees.
</P>
<P>
The details of the free education system were to be provided
for by a separate law. However, owing to various reasons, the
Governor of Macao did not issue an act on free education until
1995.
</P>
<P>
That free education act provides that pupils of the seven
grades from the pre-school class to grade 6 class of the primary
schools shall enjoy free education starting from the 1995-1996
school year, provided that they are from the government-funded
schools or non-profit-seeking private schools.
</P>
<P>
But compulsory education is different from free education. In
addition to offering education free, it stresses the right of
every school-age child to receive education and the obligation of
the government and parents to create conditions for children to
receive education. Apparently, compulsory education is not yet
practiced in Macao.
</P>
<P>
In the course of drafting the Basic Law, the drafting
committee gave careful consideration to the demand of the Macao
residents for replacing free education with compulsory education.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that without adequate financial resources, it
will be difficult to introduce compulsory education. It is
therefore stipulated in Article 121 of the Basic Law that the
Government of the Macao Special Administrative Region shall, in
accordance with law, gradually institute a compulsory educational
system.
</P>
<P>
This provision places both the Government of the Macao Special
Administrative Region under a legal obligation to pursue
compulsory education and to take into account the interests of all
sections of society.
</P>
<P>
It makes it possible for compulsory education to gradually
develop and improve in Macao under rule of law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
