<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Asia Film Festival to be Held in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC) Film Festival, the first of its kind,
will be held in Sri Lanka in September this year to boost
interaction within the region.
</P>
<P>
The two-week festival, based on a concept of Sri Lankan
President Chandrika Kumaratunga, will be held in Colombo and will
screen films produced after January 1, 1996 from all the SAARC
nations, officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
They said these films with English subtitles will not be
screened on a competitive basis and will provide a much needed
boost to films in countries such as Nepal, Bangladesh and Bhutan
and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
However, there is strong possibility that these films will be
held on a competitive basis in the years to come in the lines of
the Khan Film Festival in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The festival will screen both feature films and documentaries
as well as short films. It will carry on annually in other SAARC
capitals.
</P>
<P>
President Kumaratunga has directed the Ministry of Posts,
Telecommunications and the Media to coordinate the preliminary
arrangements with the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the SAARC
Secretariat and the Colombo-based Asian Film Center.
</P>
<P>
A high powered eight-member committee headed by Secretary to
the Ministry of Posts, Telecommunications and the Media K.C.
Logeswaran, has been appointed to coordinate the arrangements
leading to the festival.
</P>
<P>
SAARC groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Nepal, Pakistan, the
Maldives and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
