<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, April 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World
Bank will take actions to strengthen the Heavily Indebted Poor
Countries (HIPC) Initiative, a senior IMF official said here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Tony Boote, in charge of the initiative at the IMF, said the
debt relief program for the world's most debt-ridden countries has
failed to live up to expectations and needs much work.
</P>
<P>
The HIPC Initiative, launched in the fall of 1996, represented
a major departure from past practice in dealing with debt problems
of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
It focused on achieving overall external debt-sustainability
with comprehensive participation by all external creditors for the
most heavily indebted countries with good track record.
</P>
<P>
The program initially promised debt relief to 23 countries,
with proposals to broaden it to 41 countries with total debt of $
200 billion. (US-IMF-HIPC)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The Dow Jones industrial average fell Friday as
investors took profits after a three day rally.
</P>
<P>
The Dow closed down 37.51 at 10,689.67. The blue chip stocks
rose 286.65 points in the past three days and investors sell
stocks today to lock in their gains.
</P>
<P>
But the technology heavy Nasdaq index rose 29.08 to 2,590.69
as Gateway 2000 reported strong earnings. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index rose 1.97 to 1,356.85.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 1.67 to 639.30. But the American
Stock Exchange composite index rose 11.98 to 770.36 and the
Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 2.97 to 431.82. (
Wall Street-Stocks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- The Andean Development Corporation ( CAF) floated its
first issue of bonds for 300 million euros in the London and
Frankfurt markets, with the most competitive interest rate ever
issued by a Latin American bond company.
</P>
<P>
A CAF publication says that this issue in euros seeks to
continue the financial diversification strategy aimed at boosting
investments in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The issue in euros has a five year maturity and 4.75 percent
interest.
</P>
<P>
This is the eighth issue of the kind made by CAF, and it has
already put in the market 1.2 billion U.S. dollars, as reported by
the corporation. (CAF-Bonds)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- The World Bank (WB) is concerned about the
risk existing in the western economies, a senior WB official said
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Uri Dadush, director of WB Development Outlook Group, told a
seminar on the world economy outlook that the WB has a cautious
optimism about the world economy recovery due to the improvement
in southeast Asia and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
He said that the biggest danger in the short term could occur
in the industrialized countries. (World Bank-Western Economies)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- Myanmar produced 51,791 tons of sugar in 1998,
according to the latest Economic Indicators published by the
country's Central Statistical Organization.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar cultivates over 100,000 hectares of sugarcane with an
output of over 5 million tons annually.
</P>
<P>
Sugar production of the country remained steady for the past
three years, maintaining at over 50,000 tons annually.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar Ministry of Agriculture and Irrigation has adopted
some measures to increase sugar production by disbursing loan and
granting advanced payment to sugarcane growers. (Myanmar-Sugar)
</P>
</TEXT>
