<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Reaffirms Rejection to Deployment of Foreign Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivorad
Jovanovic on Friday reiterated the opposition to the deployment of
international forces in Kosovo, according to the Itar-Tass news
agency.
</P>
<P>
Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin and Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic did not talk about the issue of "international
military presence" in Kosovo during their meeting on Wednesday, a
senior Yugoslav diplomat, on behalf of Jovanovic, told the
Belgrade bureau of Itar-Tass. They just discussed the possibility
of sending civil staff to Kosovo, he said.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat also expressed his dissatisfaction over some media
reports saying that "Yugoslavia has agreed to the deployment of
'international presence' under the U.N. flag and with the
participation of Russia."
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin flew to Belgrade Thursday for talks with Milosevic
on seeking a peaceful solution to the Kosovo crisis. According to
Itar-Tass, the envoy unveiled Thursday night before departure that
Russia and Yugoslavia were preparing to sign a joint document on
the idea of accepting "international presence" in Kosovo. The
details on the nature and makeup of the international presence
needed further discussion, Chernomyrdin was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Chernomyrdin reaffirmed Yugoslavia's concession of
allowing the deployment of foreign "military troops" in Kosovo but
meanwhile stressed the formation of those troops "should be agreed
by Yugoslavia," reported the Itar-Tass.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Washington, where NATO summit is
being held to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the alliance, U.S.
president Bill Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair on
the same day rejected the reported concession of Milosevic as
insufficient and claimed to continue military attacks against his
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
