<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Al-Qathafi's Son Meets Philippines' MILF Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A son of Libyan leader Omar
Al-Qathafi met Friday with Philippines' Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF) leader Hashim Salamat in a jungle camp of the MILF in
an effort to jump-start peace talks between the rebel organization
and the Philippine government, the Philippine Star reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, Saif al-Islam al-Qathafi was
accompanied by the Libyan ambassador and two close aides of
Philippine President Joseph Estrada during the visit to a main
training base of the MILF outside the southern city of Cotabato.
</P>
<P>
"Qathafi asked Salamat to hasten the peace talks with Manila,"
MILF spokesman Mohacquer Iqbal was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"On our side, there is no problem because we are sincere.
There's a saying that it takes two to tango so we need sincerity
on the part of the government," he added.
</P>
<P>
The younger Qathafi stayed in the MILF's camp for about three
hours and attended weekly prayers.
</P>
<P>
Another MILF spokesman, Shariff Julabbi, said committee-level
talks to set the agenda for formal peace negotiations were now to
be held on May 8-9 in Cotabato instead of the last week in April.
</P>
<P>
It will be the final meeting of the technical committees from
both sides. Formal peace negotiations to seek a political solution
to the 21-year-old hostilities between MILF and the government are
set to open later in May, Julabbi said.
</P>
<P>
The 12,000-strong MILF was left out in a peace treaty that
Manila signed with the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) in
1996, which ended that group's 24-year armed struggle for an
independent Muslim state in the main southern island of Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Libya and the Organization of the Islamic Conference played key
roles in the successful peace negotiations between the Philippine
government and the MNLF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
