<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Album On Work Of American Agronomist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- An album of the life of William
Hinton, an American agronomist who worked in China, has just been
released by a Hong Kong publisher.
</P>
<P>
"Hinton: An Old Friend of the Chinese People" has seven
chapters and more than 200 photos of Hinton's life and work in
China. It was compiled by the Communist Party Committee of the
city of Changzhi in Shanxi Province where Hinton spent a year in
1948 with a group of university teachers studying land reforms in
a local village.
</P>
<P>
Hinton was born in Chicago in 1919 and came to China as a
volunteer in 1947 to train China's first group of people using
farm machinery. He later went to teach English at Northern
University in the southeastern part of Shanxi Province. He
returned to the U.S. in 1953.
</P>
<P>
In 1966, Hinton, who is best known in China by the name "Han
Ding", began writing books based on his experiences to explain
China's revolution and development to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Hinton will turn 80 this year. He had met Chinese leaders of
the past like Mao Zedong, Zhou Enlai, and Deng Xiaoping, who spoke
highly of his outstanding contributions to Sino-U.S. friendship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
