<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Works out New Policies for Industrial Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government is making
efforts to help its industrial zones (IZs) succeed by working out
new policies on domestic and overseas investment in the zone.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's 63 IZs need 20-25 billion U.S. dollars to widen their
operations, but the Vietnamese authorities feel that this is
beyond the country's economic capabilities. They therefore hope to
reap 70-80 percent of this sum from foreign direct investment,
according to a report of Vietnam's English newspaper Vietnam News
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government has focused on adjusting policies in
response to investors' complaints about the investment environment
and overly complicated procedures, the paper quoted an official of
the Vietnam Industrial Zone Management board as saying.
</P>
<P>
In addition, local authorities have adjusted some regulations
to make the IZs more attractive, especially by reducing taxes on
rented land. IZs in Hai Phong, Hanoi and Binh Duong Province are
among those that have cut such taxes by 40-50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Businesses in the IZs have also received extensions on their
State turnover tax payments to boost production and ease problems
of investment forms and cash flow.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, IZ-based businesses have had their import tax on
accessories and technological equipment waived or reduced.
</P>
<P>
The IZs have also been allowed access to the domestic market
and simplified customs procedures.
</P>
<P>
The government, relevant ministries and bodies, local
authorities and investors must coordinate their efforts to help
IZs succeed, the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
