<HEADLINE> Panama, Colombia to Reinforce Border Surveillance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Panamanian Foreign Minister
Jorge Eduardo Ritter said on Friday that Panama and Colombia
agreed to reinforce surveillance along their shared borders.
</P>
<P>
The agreement came amid press reports that armed
confrontations have occurred in the border area between the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC) guerrillas, the
Colombian Army and paramilitary forces.
</P>
<P>
Panama could hardly agree on the creation of a joint military
force, because it has no army since the old Defense Force was
dismantled in 1989.
</P>
<P>
"So far we do not intend, nor will (we) intend to establish
joint forces," Ritter said after the closing of the Ninth Meeting
of the Colombia-Panama Neighborhood Commission.
</P>
<P>
Another agreement reached at the meeting is concerning the
establishment of a mechanism to handle emergency situations in the
border area.
</P>
<P>
"We need the good will of the two countries to solve the
problems that could emerge at the border," said Colombian Foreign
Minister Guillermo Fernandez de Soto, who also attended the
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
