<HEADLINE> Russia Accuses NATO of Human Rights Violations in Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Russia has lodged a protest with
NATO countries over human rights violations committed by NATO
forces in Yugoslavia, a Russian foreign ministry statement said on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The statement said NATO's bombing against Yugoslavia was a
blatant violation of universally recognized norms and laws
governing international affairs, adding that Russia considered
NATO's act as an aggression in which NATO must be held responsible
for all consequences arising therefrom.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that it was NATO's military actions that caused
such a huge wave of refugees and tension in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
NATO's call to overthrow the legitimately-elected leader of
Yugoslavia and intensify its military actions was even more
worrisome, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
It urged NATO to make an assessment of civilian casualties and
economic losses caused by the military actions in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
It also said Russia hoped to know when and with what measures
NATO is going to stop or correct its act of human rights
violations and how it is going to compensate for the economic
losses to Yugoslavia and its people.
</P>
<P>
Also on Friday, the U.N. Human Rights Commission in Geneva
rejected a Russia-backed motion calling for an immediate end to
hostilities and human rights violations throughout Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
