<HEADLINE> Central Intelligence Unit Set up in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Customs Department
has set up a Central Intelligence Unit (CIU) to nab local and
international racketeers who use the country as a safe haven and a
transit hub for smuggling, the official Daily news reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The CIU introduced a 24-hour public information hot-line to
receive information and two customs officers are in charge of the
hot-line to transmit intelligence immediately to the relevant
sections.
</P>
<P>
The CIU has formed intelligence networks with foreign customs
in order to strengthen detection of international smuggling
through the country.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the informants were rather hesitant because a proper
channel to reach the correct person in time was not available and
they had to contact a friend or someone to prove the authenticity
of the information, customs officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, in the new unit there will be a round-the-clock
answering service and a team on call to pursue the "leads".
</P>
<P>
The CIU also plans to recruit informants on a permanent basis
to assist in the detection, the officials told the paper Friday.
</P>
<P>
About 40 percent of the annual detection by the Sri Lankan
Customs are made on public information in Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
