<HEADLINE> Oceanic Disasters Cause Great Loss to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The oceanic disasters last year
caused more than two billion yuan (about 241 million U.S. dollars)
of losses in China's coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
These disasters were mainly typhoons, tidal waves, ice and red
tides, said Wang Fei, director of the environmental protection
department under the State Oceanic Administration.
</P>
<P>
Seven big typhoons occurred along the coast over the past year,
three of which caused huge damages and about one billion yuan of
direct economic losses.
</P>
<P>
About 22 red tides appeared in 1998, affecting not only the
coastal sea areas but also some outer seas.
</P>
<P>
The duration of the red tides last year was much longer than
ever before, Wang said. The biggest red tide ever recorded in the
Bohai Sea took place last fall, lasting over 40 days and affecting
an area of 5,000 square kilometers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
