<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Suffers Economic Losses by NATO Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 23 (Xinhua) -- NATO's month-long bombing of
Yugoslavia has caused a loss of 700.3 million U.S. dollars to the
Romanian economy, Romanian Prime Minister Radu Vasile announced on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
 He said his government has handed over a report on the loss
situation to the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The news media here quoted the IMF as saying that the Romanian
gross domestic product of this year may drop two percentage points
due to the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
Experts of the World Economic Institute in Bucharest believe
that the Kosovo crisis will inflict both short-term and long-term
losses on Romanian economy.
</P>
<P>
As for short-term losses, they noted that the cooperation
between Romania and Yugoslavia that was resumed following an end
to the sanctions against Yugoslavia not long ago will have to be
stopped. The suspension of traffic on the Danube River raised the
costs of Romanian exports to western Europe, therefore forcing
many of its products to quit this profitable market.
</P>
<P>
The long-term impact is even worse, they said. International
investors will lose confidence and sense of security in the
turbulent Balkan region, which therefore may dampen Romanian
efforts to reinvigorate its economy.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that during international sanctions against
Yugoslavia from 1992 to 1995, Romania suffered a total loss of 30
billion dollars, including over seven billion dollars of immediate
losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990424.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Enjoys Clearing Skies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The increasing frequency of
blue skies and white clouds in Guangzhou, the bustling capital of
south China's Guangdong Province, has resulted in fewer complaints
about urban pollution.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the municipal environment monitoring
center show that the air quality was good or equal to second-
degree national standards for 14 weeks last year.
</P>
<P>
The improving air quality has been attributed to the city
government's incessant efforts to curb urban pollution. Guangzhou
was one of the first group of Chinese cities to introduce weekly
air quality reports. The city also banned the use of leaded
gasoline.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou is working diligently to become a model Chinese city
using liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) and environmentally-friendly
fuel. The city has allocated two million yuan to construct two LPG
fueling stations and replace old shuttle buses with new units
equipped for LPG.
</P>
<P>
A number of industrial pollutant indices, including sulfur
dioxide, carbon monoxide and nitrogen oxide, has dropped owing to
the fact that 93 percent of industrial plants have either improved
waste gas treatment facilities or otherwise moved out of the urban
area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
