<HEADLINE> Jayasinghe Hearing Adjourned to July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The doping hearing against woman
sprinter Susanthika Jayasinghe of Sri Lanka has been adjourned
until July, the track and field's world governing body IAAF said
in Monte Carlo, Monaco on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Jayasinghe, 24, was tested positive for the steroid nandrolone
in a random doping test in last April, and would face a two-year
ban.
</P>
<P>
IAAF spokesman Giorgio Reineri said Jayasinghe, flanked by a
large Sri Lankan contingent, appeared in the hearing on Thursday,
presented new evidence that forced the three-member doping panel
to adjourn the case to a date in July.
</P>
<P>
Jayasinghe, who won a silver medal in the 200 meters at the
1997 world championships in Athens, left Sri Lanka for training in
the United States after the Asian Games in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
However, Jayasinghe, even if being found guilty and banned for
two years, could still compete at the Sydney 2000 Olympics as the
bans are usually considered to take effect from the date that the
athlete was caught.
</P>
<P>
Reineri said Jayasinghe was entitled to keep competing because
she was cleared by her federation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
