<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Infrastructure Construction Encouraged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China is to provide a vast stable
market for foreign investment in the infrastructure construction
sector, according to Song Mi, a senior official with the State
Development Planning Commission (SDPC).
</P>
<P>
Song, who is in charge of the development of basic industries,
said that more importance will be attached to the energy and
transportation sectors this year and that more foreign investment
is welcome.
</P>
<P>
"Existing foreign investment agreements and contracts will be
honored until they expire," Song said, adding that any
infringements will be severely punished.
</P>
<P>
"However, preferential policies aimed at promoting
infrastructure construction may vary according to the actual
market conditions," she said.
</P>
<P>
Song also gave a list of key industries which will undergo a
structural readjustment, including power generation, coal,
petroleum and natural gas, liquefied natural gas, railways and
highways.
</P>
<P>
China has stepped up input in infrastructure construction last
year in an effort to stimulate domestic demand. Investment in the
coal, electricity, petroleum, communications and
telecommunications sectors totaled 878 billion yuan (about 106
billion U.S.dollars), surging 29 percent year on year.
</P>
</TEXT>
