<HEADLINE> U.S. to Deploy 2,000 More Troops for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Pentagon said on Friday it
would deploy more than 2,000 extra troops to the Balkans and more
equipment to strengthen the air campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
A Pentagon spokesman told reporters that the troops will come
from U.S. bases in Europe and the United States to augment the
Apache strike helicopters joining the NATO force.
</P>
<P>
More missile batteries and armored vehicles were being sent at
the request of NATO's supreme Allied Commander, Gen. Wesley Clark,
to support the 24 Apaches now in Albania, said the Pentagon
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The Apache helicopters arrived in Tirana, the capital of
Albania, earlier this week and have not been used in any combat
operation.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon also said that the troops will help protect the
Apaches while they are on the ground, but will not accompany the
Apaches on missions inside Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The new deployment will bring U.S. troop level in the region to
5,350, the Pentagon said. 
</P>
