<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agriculture Calls for High-Tech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- In a major effort to accelerate
the application of laboratory results to agriculture, the Chinese
government has kicked off a new project called "Crossing Program"
backed with an annual funding of 50 million yuan (six million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The project was launched by the ministries of agriculture and
finance to meet farmers urgent needs for new technology to help
them boost production and income, today's "China Daily" says.
</P>
<P>
Chinese farmers have been complaining that while agro-science
and research achievements are reported in the media, they remain
either in laboratories or small pilot farms - beyond the reach of
those working in the fields.
</P>
<P>
Now this "Crossing Program" is designed to bring these new
technologies to the farms as soon as possible, ministry officials
said.
</P>
<P>
"Agriculture production has benefited more and more from
science in past few years, but the country has yet to speed up
conversion of research into productivity, and improve science's
contribution to agricultural output," Vice-Minister of Agriculture
Lu Ming was quoted by the paper as saying yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the channel for the implementation of agro-science
and new technologies is somewhat "obstructed", the vice-minister
said at a ceremony in Beijing launching the "Crossing Program".
</P>
<P>
The "Crossing Program" makes sure that the country's "Bumper
Harvest Plan" will have sufficient practical and advanced
technological tools to apply, Lu said.
</P>
<P>
In the long run, the new program will contribute to the
sustainable development of agriculture in a country that is
striving to ensure security of food supply. It also pursues the
strategy of "revitalizing the nation through science and education,
" he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
