<HEADLINE> Moya Upset in Monte Carlo Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Carlos Moya was beaten by
unseeded Jerome Golmard in the quarterfinals for the biggest upset
in the Monte Carlo Open on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Spaniard Moya suffered the defeat as Golmard of France won for
the first time in a Super 9 tennis tournament with a determined 6-
7 (5-7), 6-3, 6-0 triumph.
</P>
<P>
In the semifinals of the dlrs 2.2 million event, the French
left-hander will play No. 9 seed Marcelo Rios, who defeated Mark
Philippoussis of Australia 6-2, 6-7 (2-7), 6-4.
</P>
<P>
No. 13 seed Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil faces Spain's Felix
Mantilla, seeded 15, in the other semifinal.
</P>
<P>
In one of the biggest upsets of the tournament, Moya never
looked at ease and could do little to stop his game from
collapsing in the final set.
</P>
<P>
Moya who ranked second, took 67 minutes to win the first set
but lost the following two sets in 62 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Golmard, guaranteed to be the new French No. 1 next week, has
now won all three encounters against Moya, though this was the
first on Moya's favorite clay surface.
</P>
<P>
Mantilla won a tight match against countryman Albert Costa 6-4,
6-7 (2-7), 7-6 (7-4), in two hours 46 minutes, after Costa wasted
four match points in the final set, and Kuerten was too strong for
American Vince Spadea, winning 6-3, 6-3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
