<HEADLINE> Thailand's Trade Surplus Narrows in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's trade surplus narrowed
 in March this year to its lowest level in 18 months as a rise in
imports wasn't matched by exports.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus shrank to 536 million U.S. dollars, falling
39 percent from the same month a year ago and 8.8 percent from
February, according to figures released by the Thai Finance
Ministry available here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The country's import rose 6.8 percent from a year earlier and
17 percent from February to 4.26 billion dollars, the highest
level since October 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Exports fell 1.4 percent, but rose 13 percent from
February, to 4.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that the increased imports may signal a
recovery in domestic demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
