<HEADLINE> Myanmar Produces Over 50,000 Tons of Sugar in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar produced 51,791 tons of
sugar in 1998, according to the latest Economic Indicators
published by the country's Central Statistical Organization.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar cultivates over 100,000 hectares of sugarcane with an
output of over 5 million tons annually.
</P>
<P>
Sugar production of the country remained steady for the past
three years, maintaining at over 50,000 tons annually.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar Ministry of Agriculture and Irrigation has adopted
some measures to increase sugar production by disbursing loan and
granting advanced payment to sugarcane growers.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, the Myanmar government has
been allowing the private sector to reclaim vacant, virgin, fallow
and wetlands for cultivation of industrial raw material crops
including sugarcane, jute, cotton, Virginia tobacco and coffee.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the state-run Myanmar Sugarcane Enterprise (MSE) has
 been building ten more sugar mills in recent years in the areas
of Paukkaung, Pyay and Aunglan in Bago and Magway divisions where
there are enough sugarcane resources.
</P>
<P>
Some of these on-going sugar mill projects are implemented by
companies from China and Thailand under contracts signed with the
MSE in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar exports over 35,000 tons of sugar annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
