<HEADLINE> Maloney Supports Cardiff Bid for Boxing Bout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Welsh Rugby Union is stepping
up its campaign to stage the Lennox Lewis-Evander Holyfield
rematch at the new Millennium Stadium in Cardiff - and it has the
backing of Lewis' manager Frank Maloney.
</P>
<P>
Although Las Vegas and New York are hot favourites to host the
heavyweight unification battle, pencilled in for November, Maloney
is keen to see the bout go ahead in the city where his man
defeated Frank Bruno back in 1993.
</P>
<P>
He was in Wales to inspect the site in the company of WRU
chairman Glanmor Griffiths and insisted that Cardiff would be his
personal choice.
</P>
<P>
Maloney said that if the money was available American promoter
Don King would agree too.
</P>
<P>
"I'll be sending Don a presentation pack about the new stadium
and inviting him to come and see it for himself," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure he'd be as impressed as I was, "added Maloney. "From
what I've seen, it's going to be a great place. It's intimidating,
which is fantastic, and with the roof there'll be no problem about
a 4am start."
</P>
<P>
WRU chief Griffiths stressed that the capacity of 72,500 would
make it the largest covered arena in the world and he said
November 13 - one of the dates suggested by American cable network
Home Box Office - would be perfect for the bout. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
